  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For follicular neoplasms, the scalpel provides the final answer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Left hemithyroidectomy. A suspicious follicular neoplasm (Bethesda IV) on FNA cytology indicates a significant risk of malignancy (15-30%) and requires surgical excision for definitive diagnosis and potential treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFollicular neoplasms cannot be definitively diagnosed as benign (adenoma) or malignant (carcinoma) by FNA alone, as the distinction relies on the presence of capsular or vascular invasion, which can only be assessed histologically. A diagnostic hemithyroidectomy provides the necessary tissue for pathological evaluation while preserving the contralateral lobe, potentially avoiding lifelong thyroid hormone replacement if the lesion proves benign.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Repeat FNA) (Incorrect): A suspicious follicular neoplasm (Bethesda IV) has a significant risk of malignancy, and repeating FNA is unlikely to change the diagnosis, thus delaying definitive management.\nOption C (Prescribe thyroxine) (Incorrect): Thyroxine suppression therapy is not recommended for suspicious thyroid nodules as it does not reliably shrink malignant lesions and delays definitive diagnosis.\nOption D (Radioactive ablation) (Incorrect): Radioactive iodine ablation is a treatment for differentiated thyroid cancer *after* surgical removal, not an initial management strategy for a suspicious mass.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Bethesda Category | Risk of Malignancy | Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| I (Non-diagnostic) | 5-10% | Repeat FNA with US guidance |\n| II (Benign) | 0-3% | Clinical follow-up |\n| III (Atypia of Undetermined Significance/FLUS) | 5-15% | Repeat FNA, molecular testing, or diagnostic lobectomy |\n| IV (Follicular Neoplasm/Suspicious for Follicular Neoplasm) | 15-30% | Diagnostic lobectomy/Hemithyroidectomy |\n| V (Suspicious for Malignancy) | 60-75% | Near-total or total thyroidectomy |\n| VI (Malignant) | 97-99% | Total thyroidectomy (or lobectomy for low-risk microcarcinoma) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Follicular neoplasm on FNA = diagnostic lobectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a 'cold mass' (referring to hypofunction on scintigraphy) might appear as a solid, hypoechoic nodule with irregular margins or microcalcifications, though follicular neoplasms can have varied sonographic features. Intraoperatively, the surgeon would identify the left thyroid lobe containing the 1.5x2 cm mass, carefully dissect it, and perform a hemithyroidectomy, ensuring meticulous preservation of the recurrent laryngeal nerve and parathyroid glands.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (e.g., 2015 or more recent editions).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Left hemithyroidectomy. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Repeat FNA. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Prescribe thyroxine. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Radioactive ablation. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Follicular neoplasm = Bethesda 4, so go for hemithyroidectomy.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
