  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Tongue out, cyst up? Thyroglossal duct's strut!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Thyroglossal cyst. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the classic presentation of a painless, midline neck nodule in a child that moves both with swallowing and, crucially, with tongue protrusion, reflecting its embryological origin.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe thyroglossal duct is an embryological remnant from the descent of the thyroid gland from the foramen cecum at the base of the tongue to its final position in the neck. If this duct fails to involute, it can form a cyst anywhere along its path, most commonly near the hyoid bone. The characteristic movement with tongue protrusion occurs because the cyst remains tethered to the base of the tongue via the persistent duct, often passing through or intimately associated with the hyoid bone.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Dermoid cyst) (Incorrect): While often midline, dermoid cysts are typically subcutaneous and do not move with tongue protrusion as they lack connection to deeper structures like the tongue base.\nOption B (Thyroid nodule) (Incorrect): A thyroid nodule would move with swallowing due to its attachment to the trachea, but not with tongue protrusion. It's also typically lower in the neck.\nOption D (Parathyroid nodule) (Incorrect): Parathyroid nodules are usually small, deep to the thyroid, and rarely palpable. They would not exhibit movement with tongue protrusion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Thyroglossal Cyst | Dermoid Cyst | Branchial Cleft Cyst |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Location** | Midline, often near hyoid | Midline or lateral, subcutaneous | Lateral neck, anterior to SCM |\n| **Movement** | With swallowing AND tongue protrusion | No movement with tongue/swallowing | No movement with tongue/swallowing |\n| **Origin** | Remnant of thyroglossal duct | Ectodermal/mesodermal inclusion | Remnant of branchial arches |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Midline neck mass + tongue protrusion = Thyroglossal cyst.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, a thyroglossal duct cyst appears as a well-defined, anechoic or hypoechoic (on US) or fluid-filled (on CT) lesion, typically midline and often intimately associated with the hyoid bone. Intraoperatively, the Sistrunk procedure involves excising the cyst, the central portion of the hyoid bone, and the tract up to the foramen cecum to prevent recurrence.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Thyroglossal Duct Cyst (2019). It recommends surgical excision (Sistrunk procedure) for symptomatic or recurrent cysts.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Dermoid cyst. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Thyroid nodule. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Thyroglossal cyst. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Parathyroid nodule. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Midline mass and moves with tongue protrusion. Another recall asking about management? Go with surge** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
