  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, core it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is core biopsy because a BI-RADS V lesion indicates a high probability of malignancy, necessitating tissue diagnosis before definitive surgical planning. Core biopsy is the standard initial diagnostic procedure for suspicious breast masses.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCore needle biopsy is preferred over excisional biopsy for suspicious breast lesions (BI-RADS V) because it is less invasive, can be performed under imaging guidance, and provides sufficient tissue for histological diagnosis, immunohistochemical staining (e.g., ER/PR/HER2), and genetic testing. This information is crucial for treatment planning (e.g., neoadjuvant chemotherapy) and avoids unnecessary surgery or disfigurement if the lesion proves benign or requires a different surgical approach.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Excisional biopsy) (Incorrect): While diagnostic, it is more invasive than core biopsy and may unnecessarily remove a benign lesion or compromise future surgical planning if malignancy is confirmed. It's not the initial next step for diagnosis.\nOption C (Modified radical mastectomy) (Incorrect): This is a definitive surgical treatment for breast cancer and is premature without a confirmed tissue diagnosis and proper staging. Performing it without biopsy results is malpractice.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Biopsy Type | Indication | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Fine Needle Aspiration (FNA) | Cystic lesions, palpable masses (initial assessment) | Least invasive, quick results | Limited tissue, cannot distinguish invasive from in situ, high false negative rate |\n| Core Needle Biopsy (CNB) | Solid suspicious masses (BI-RADS 4/5), microcalcifications | Provides tissue architecture, allows receptor testing, less invasive than excisional | Can miss small lesions, potential for hematoma |\n| Excisional Biopsy | Persistent suspicious lesions after CNB, discordant results, small lesions | Provides definitive diagnosis, removes entire lesion | More invasive, potential for scarring/deformity, may complicate definitive surgery |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: BI-RADS V means biopsy, not immediate surgery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammogram, a BI-RADS V lesion typically presents as a spiculated mass with associated suspicious microcalcifications, indicating a high probability of malignancy. Axillary lymph node involvement further raises suspicion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer (2023). These guidelines recommend core needle biopsy as the standard for tissue diagnosis of suspicious breast lesions (BI-RADS 4/5).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Excisional biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | core Biopsy | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Modified radical mastectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Core needle biopsy, also referred to as true-cut biopsy in some recalls. Be sure to review the BI-RA** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
