  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For a giant phyllodes, simple mastectomy is the simple solution.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is simple mastectomy. For a large phyllodes tumor measuring 15x15 cm, achieving adequate clear margins with breast-conserving surgery is often not feasible, necessitating a simple mastectomy to ensure complete tumor removal and minimize local recurrence.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPhyllodes tumors are fibroepithelial tumors of the breast that can be benign, borderline, or malignant. Regardless of their histological classification, the primary treatment is surgical excision with wide clear margins (ideally at least 1 cm) due to their propensity for local recurrence. For very large tumors, such as the 15x15 cm mass described, breast-conserving surgery would result in significant cosmetic deformity and likely positive margins. Therefore, a simple mastectomy, which removes all breast tissue but preserves the pectoralis muscle and axillary lymph nodes, is the appropriate surgical approach. Axillary lymph node dissection is generally not indicated as lymph node metastasis is exceedingly rare in phyllodes tumors.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (chemo) (Incorrect): Chemotherapy has a very limited role in phyllodes tumors, primarily reserved for rare cases of metastatic disease, not as a primary treatment for localized disease.\nOption B (radio) (Incorrect): Radiotherapy is not a primary treatment for phyllodes tumors. Its role is controversial and may be considered in select cases of malignant phyllodes with positive or very close margins, or for local control in recurrent disease, but not as initial management.\nOption D (MRM) (Incorrect): Modified Radical Mastectomy (MRM) includes axillary lymph node dissection. Axillary lymph node involvement is extremely rare in phyllodes tumors, even malignant ones, making axillary dissection unnecessary and associated with avoidable morbidity.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Benign Phyllodes Tumor | Malignant Phyllodes Tumor | Large Phyllodes Tumor (e.g., 15cm) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Primary Treatment | Wide local excision (WLE) with 1cm margins | Wide local excision (WLE) with 1cm margins | Simple Mastectomy (if WLE not feasible) |\n| Adjuvant Chemo | No | Consider for metastatic disease | No (unless metastatic) |\n| Adjuvant Radiation | No | Consider for positive/close margins, large size | Consider for positive/close margins |\n| Axillary Dissection | No | No (unless clinically positive nodes) | No |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Large phyllodes tumors require simple mastectomy; axillary dissection is rarely indicated.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, phyllodes tumors often appear as large, rapidly growing, well-circumscribed, lobulated masses, sometimes with cystic components. Intraoperatively, they are typically firm, often with a characteristic 'leaf-like' or 'phyllodes' appearance on cut section, which can include areas of hemorrhage or necrosis in higher-grade tumors.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (e.g., 2023) recommend wide local excision with clear margins (at least 1 cm) for phyllodes tumors. Mastectomy is indicated if clear margins cannot be achieved with breast-conserving surgery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | chemo | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | radio | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | mastectomy | ✅ Correct |\n| D | MRM | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) As explained at the start of this section, we go for a simple mastectomy due to the size.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
