  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fifty-three? Biennial mammogram, that's the rule!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C, recommending a mammogram every two years, is the correct answer for a 53-year-old woman with a normal screening mammogram. This aligns with the United States Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) guidelines for women in this age group.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMammography screening aims to detect breast cancer early, improving prognosis. The recommended interval for screening changes with age due to varying breast cancer incidence rates and breast tissue density. For women aged 50-74, the USPSTF recommends biennial screening, as the benefits of early detection continue to outweigh potential harms like false positives, and the incidence of aggressive cancers that would be missed by a two-year interval is lower than in younger populations. This interval balances early detection with minimizing radiation exposure and unnecessary biopsies.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (6m) (Incorrect): A 6-month interval is too frequent for average-risk screening and is typically reserved for high-risk surveillance or follow-up of suspicious findings.\nOption B (1y) (Incorrect): Annual screening is generally recommended for women aged 40-49 by organizations like the American College of Radiology (ACR) and American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG), and for women over 50 by some, but the USPSTF specifically recommends biennial for 50-74.\nOption D (3y) (Incorrect): A 3-year interval is too long for routine screening in this age group, potentially delaying cancer detection and reducing the benefits of screening.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Age Group | Screening Frequency | Primary Guideline/Recommendation |\n|---|---|---|\n| 40-49 years | Annual | ACOG, ACR |\n| 50-74 years | Biennial | USPSTF |\n| 50+ years | Annual | ACOG, ACR (alternative recommendation) |\n| >75 years | Individualized | USPSTF, ACOG (based on health and life expectancy) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: USPSTF recommends biennial mammograms for women 50-74.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA normal mammogram typically shows no suspicious masses, microcalcifications, architectural distortion, or skin/nipple retraction. The breast tissue density is usually categorized (e.g., ACR BI-RADS A, B, C, D), and a normal report indicates no findings requiring further workup.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe United States Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) 2016 recommendations (and 2024 draft) advise biennial screening mammography for women aged 50 to 74 years.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 6m | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 1y | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 2y | ✅ Correct |\n| D | 3y | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Mammography screening is done annually in the range of 40 to 50 years old. Afterwards, every two yea** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
