  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just watch ADH; cut it out to be sure!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Atypical ductal hyperplasia (ADH) found on core needle biopsy necessitates surgical excision due to a significant risk of upgrade to ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) or invasive carcinoma upon definitive pathology. This approach ensures complete diagnosis and appropriate management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAtypical ductal hyperplasia (ADH) is a high-risk benign breast lesion that carries a 10-20% risk of upgrade to DCIS or invasive cancer when found on core needle biopsy. The core needle biopsy, while diagnostic, samples only a small portion of the lesion. Therefore, a wide surgical excision (also known as excisional biopsy) is performed to remove the entire area of concern, allowing for thorough pathological evaluation and ensuring that no higher-grade malignancy is missed. This management strategy is crucial for accurate diagnosis and risk stratification.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Simple mastectomy) (Incorrect): Simple mastectomy is an overtreatment for atypical ductal hyperplasia. It is typically reserved for extensive DCIS, invasive cancer, or as a prophylactic measure in very high-risk individuals, not for ADH alone.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Lesion Type | Core Biopsy Finding | Recommended Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Atypical Ductal Hyperplasia (ADH) | ADH | Excisional Biopsy |\n| Ductal Carcinoma In Situ (DCIS) | DCIS | Lumpectomy with clear margins +/- radiation or Mastectomy |\n| Lobular Carcinoma In Situ (LCIS) | LCIS | Observation, risk reduction, or consideration of excisional biopsy |\n| Usual Ductal Hyperplasia (UDH) | UDH | Observation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: ADH on core biopsy demands excisional biopsy due to upgrade risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nMammography might show calcifications or a mass associated with ADH, but the definitive diagnosis comes from pathology. Intraoperatively, the surgeon targets the area identified on imaging, often using wire localization or radioactive seed localization. Histopathology of the excised specimen will show proliferation of epithelial cells with some architectural and cytologic atypia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Breast Surgeons (ASBrS) Consensus Guideline on the Management of Atypical Ductal Hyperplasia (2016, reaffirmed 2021) recommends surgical excision for ADH diagnosed on core needle biopsy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | wide surgical excision. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Simple mastectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) The keyword is atypical ductal hyperplasia.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
