  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 The 'breast mouse' is a young woman's best friend, not a foe.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is fibroadenoma. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the patient's young age (20 years old) and the classic description of the mass as 2x2 cm, oval in shape, and having a smooth wall, which are hallmarks of a benign, mobile breast lesion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFibroadenomas are the most common benign solid tumors of the breast, typically occurring in young women (under 30). They arise from both glandular and stromal tissue, giving them their characteristic firm, rubbery, mobile, and well-circumscribed feel on palpation, often described as a 'breast mouse.' Their oval shape and smooth borders are key features that differentiate them from malignant lesions, which tend to be irregular, fixed, and have spiculated margins.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (breast cyst) (Incorrect): While cysts can be smooth and mobile, they are typically fluid-filled and more common in perimenopausal women. A solid, oval mass in a 20-year-old is less likely to be a simple cyst.\nOption C (fibrocystic cancer) (Incorrect): 'Fibrocystic cancer' is not a recognized medical term. Fibrocystic changes are benign, while cancer is malignant. This option is a misnomer.\nOption D (intraductal carcinoma) (Incorrect): Intraductal carcinoma (DCIS) is a non-invasive form of breast cancer. While it can present as a mass, it is rare in a 20-year-old and typically presents with microcalcifications on mammography or as a palpable, often irregular, mass, not usually described as smooth and oval in this age group.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Fibroadenoma | Breast Cyst | Invasive Ductal Carcinoma (IDC) |\n| :--------------- | :----------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------- |\n| **Age Group** | Young women (15-30 years) | Perimenopausal (35-50 years) | Older women (>50 years), but can occur younger |\n| **Palpation** | Firm, rubbery, mobile, well-circumscribed, oval | Smooth, mobile, often compressible, fluid-filled | Hard, irregular, fixed, ill-defined margins |\n| **Size/Shape** | Variable, often 1-5 cm, oval | Variable, round/oval | Variable, irregular |\n| **Pain** | Usually painless | May be painful, especially pre-menstrually | Usually painless, but can cause discomfort |\n| **Management** | Observation, excision if growing/symptomatic | Aspiration, observation | Biopsy, surgery, adjuvant therapy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Young, oval, smooth, mobile breast mass = fibroadenoma until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a fibroadenoma typically appears as a well-circumscribed, oval, hypoechoic mass with a smooth capsule and often exhibits posterior acoustic enhancement. Color Doppler usually shows minimal or no internal vascularity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) BI-RADS Atlas (5th Edition, 2013). It provides standardized terminology and assessment categories for breast imaging findings, classifying fibroadenomas as typically BI-RADS 2 (benign) or BI-RADS 3 (probably benign) depending on specific features.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | breast cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | fibroadenoma | ✅ Correct |\n| C | fibrocystic cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | intraductal carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) An oval shaped mobile mass. A missing keyword is the relation between the mass and the menstrual cyc** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
