  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When a lump waxes and wanes with the moon, a cyst is often the tune.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Breast cyst. This diagnosis is strongly supported by the patient's age, the mobile and oval-shaped nature of the lump, and critically, its fluctuation in size with the menstrual cycle, which is characteristic of hormonal influence on benign cystic changes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBreast cysts are fluid-filled sacs that develop within the breast tissue, often as a result of hormonal changes, particularly estrogen. They are a common manifestation of fibrocystic changes, especially in premenopausal women. The cyclical fluctuation in size is due to hormonal variations throughout the menstrual cycle, leading to fluid accumulation and reabsorption within the cyst. These cysts are typically benign and can be mobile and smooth to palpation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Normal breast tissue in young people) (Incorrect): While young women often have dense, glandular breast tissue, a distinct, palpable lump that fluctuates with menstruation is not simply \"normal tissue\" but rather a specific benign entity.\nOption C (Fibroadenoma) (Incorrect): Fibroadenomas are common benign tumors in young women, typically mobile and rubbery. However, they generally do not fluctuate in size with the menstrual cycle, which is a key differentiating factor here.\nOption D (Phyllode) (Incorrect): Phyllodes tumors are much less common than cysts or fibroadenomas, especially in a 21-year-old. They tend to grow rapidly and can be quite large, but they do not typically exhibit cyclical size fluctuation with menstruation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Breast Cyst | Fibroadenoma | Fibrocystic Changes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Age** | 30-50s (premenopausal) | 15-35 (younger) | 20-50s (premenopausal) |\n| **Fluctuation** | Yes, with menses | No | Yes, with menses |\n| **Mobility** | Mobile | Mobile | Variable |\n| **Consistency** | Soft to firm, smooth | Rubbery, firm | Lumpy, tender |\n| **Malignant Potential** | None (simple cyst) | None | None (unless atypical hyperplasia) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cyclical breast lump fluctuation = hormonal influence, think cyst.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a simple breast cyst appears as an anechoic (black) lesion with a smooth, thin wall, posterior acoustic enhancement, and no internal vascularity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 164 (2016) on Management of Benign Breast Disease recommends clinical evaluation and imaging (ultrasound for women under 30) for palpable breast masses.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Breast cyst | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Normal breast tissue in young people | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Fibroadenoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Phyllode | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
