  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When breasts ache with the cycle, think cysts, not cancer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct answer is A, Fibrocystic. The classic presentation of multiple, bilateral breast masses that worsen prior to menses is highly indicative of benign fibrocystic changes, which are hormonally influenced.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFibrocystic changes represent a spectrum of benign alterations in breast tissue, driven primarily by fluctuations in estrogen and progesterone during the menstrual cycle. These hormonal shifts lead to epithelial hyperplasia, stromal fibrosis, and cyst formation, resulting in palpable lumps, tenderness, and pain that typically exacerbate in the luteal phase before menstruation and improve after. This cyclical nature and multifocal, bilateral presentation are hallmarks of the condition.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Fibroadenoma) (Incorrect): Fibroadenomas are typically solitary, discrete, mobile, rubbery masses that do not usually exhibit the same degree of cyclical tenderness or multiplicity as fibrocystic changes.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Fibrocystic Changes | Fibroadenoma |\n|---|---|---|\n| Presentation | Multiple, bilateral, diffuse nodularity | Solitary, discrete, well-circumscribed mass |\n| Cyclicality | Worsens pre-menses, improves post-menses | Generally non-cyclical, stable |\n| Consistency | Rubbery, firm, sometimes tender | Rubbery, firm, non-tender |\n| Mobility | Less distinct, diffuse | Highly mobile (\"breast mouse\") |\n| Age Group | 20-50s, common in perimenopausal | 15-35 years, common in younger women |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cyclical, bilateral breast pain/lumps = fibrocystic.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, fibrocystic changes often appear as multiple cysts of varying sizes, sometimes with associated stromal fibrosis or adenosis. Mammography may show diffuse increased fibroglandular density, scattered calcifications, or circumscribed masses (cysts).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) Appropriateness Criteria for Breast Pain (2017) recommends imaging (ultrasound, mammography) based on age and clinical findings to differentiate benign from malignant causes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Fibrocystic | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Fibroademoa | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "A"
