  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pregnancy makes your areola glands pop, perfectly normal, no need to stop!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Montgomery’s Follicles because these are hypertrophied sebaceous glands located in the areola, which become more prominent and visible during pregnancy and lactation due to hormonal changes. Their smooth, round, and painless presentation in a a 33-week pregnant woman perfectly matches the description.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMontgomery's glands, also known as Montgomery's tubercles or areolar glands, are modified sebaceous glands found within the areola. During pregnancy and lactation, hormonal stimulation (estrogen and progesterone) causes these glands to hypertrophy, becoming more noticeable as small, smooth, round, and painless bumps. They secrete a lipoid fluid that lubricates and protects the nipple and areola, and their scent may also help guide the infant to the nipple during breastfeeding.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (breast cyst) (Incorrect): Breast cysts are fluid-filled sacs typically found deeper within the breast tissue, not as multiple follicles around the areola. They can be painful or tender, unlike the described painless lesions.\nOption C (Lactiferous duct) (Incorrect): Lactiferous ducts are internal structures responsible for transporting milk to the nipple. They are not externally visible as \"follicles\" around the areola.\nOption D (Mondor's disease) (Incorrect): Mondor's disease is a rare condition involving thrombophlebitis of superficial veins of the breast or chest wall, presenting as a painful, palpable, cord-like structure, which is distinctly different from smooth, round, painless follicles.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Montgomery's Follicles | Breast Cyst | Mondor's Disease |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Appearance** | Small, smooth, round bumps around areola | Palpable lump, often mobile, sometimes tender | Painful, palpable, cord-like structure |\n| **Location** | Areola | Deeper breast tissue | Superficial veins of breast/chest wall |\n| **Symptoms** | Painless, benign | Can be painful/tender, fluctuate with cycle | Painful, often with skin retraction |\n| **Associated with** | Pregnancy, lactation | Hormonal changes, fibrocystic changes | Trauma, surgery, inflammation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Prominent areolar bumps in pregnancy are benign Montgomery's glands.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn physical exam, these appear as small, raised, smooth, dome-shaped papules or nodules on the areola. They are typically bilateral and symmetrical. No specific imaging is usually required as the diagnosis is clinical.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 164 (2016) - Management of Benign Breast Disease. Recommends reassurance for benign findings like Montgomery's glands.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Montgomery’s Follicles | ✅ Correct |\n| B | breast cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lactiferous duct | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Mondor's disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
