  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, biopsy it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Nipple biopsy (C). This clinical presentation of unilateral nipple dryness, crusting, and oozing, even with normal imaging, is highly suspicious for Paget's disease of the nipple, which is an intraepidermal adenocarcinoma. A biopsy is essential for definitive diagnosis and to rule out malignancy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPaget's disease of the nipple is a rare form of breast cancer characterized by the migration of malignant ductal epithelial cells (Paget cells) into the epidermis of the nipple and areola. The classic presentation includes unilateral, eczematous changes, itching, burning, crusting, scaling, and sometimes oozing or ulceration. While it can mimic benign dermatological conditions, its unilateral nature and persistence, especially when imaging is normal, demand histological evaluation. A punch biopsy or shave biopsy of the affected nipple skin is the gold standard for diagnosis, revealing the characteristic Paget cells.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Follow up US in 6 months is inappropriate. Given the suspicious clinical symptoms, delaying diagnosis for 6 months could allow a malignancy to progress. Normal imaging does not rule out Paget's disease, as it is a superficial epidermal lesion.\nOption B (Incorrect): Prescribing steroid ointment would mask the symptoms, potentially providing temporary relief but delaying the definitive diagnosis of a potentially malignant condition. This is a common pitfall in diagnosing Paget's disease, as it can initially be misdiagnosed as eczema.\nOption D (Incorrect): Referral to dermatology would also delay the definitive diagnosis. While a dermatologist might be consulted for skin conditions, in this context, the primary concern is malignancy, and a biopsy is the most direct and necessary next step, often performed by a surgeon or breast specialist.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Paget's Disease of Nipple                               | Nipple Eczema                                     | Nipple Adenoma (Florid Papillomatosis)            |\n|---------------------|---------------------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|\n| **Presentation**    | Unilateral, persistent, eczematous changes, crusting, oozing, itching, burning. Often associated with underlying DCIS/invasive cancer. | Bilateral, intermittent, itchy, red, scaly. Often history of atopy. Responds to steroids. | Nipple discharge (serous/bloody), mass, pain. Benign. |\n| **Imaging**         | Mammography/US often normal, but can show underlying mass/calcifications if associated with DCIS/invasive cancer. | Normal                                            | May show a subareolar mass on US/mammography.     |\n| **Diagnosis**       | Punch or shave biopsy of nipple skin (Paget cells).     | Clinical, response to topical steroids. Biopsy if atypical or persistent. | Excisional biopsy.                                |\n| **Management**      | Surgical excision (mastectomy or breast-conserving surgery with sentinel lymph node biopsy), adjuvant therapy based on underlying cancer. | Topical steroids, emollients.                     | Excision.                                         |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unilateral nipple changes + normal imaging = biopsy for Paget's.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (mammography and ultrasound) is often normal in early Paget's disease, as the disease is confined to the epidermis. However, it is crucial to perform imaging to rule out an underlying ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) or invasive breast cancer, which is present in 50-60% of cases. A biopsy of the nipple skin will show characteristic large, pale-staining Paget cells with prominent nucleoli within the epidermis. There are no images provided in the question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Clinical Practice Guidelines in Oncology: Breast Cancer (Version 1.2024) recommends biopsy for suspicious nipple lesions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Follow up US in 6 month. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Prescribe steroid ointment. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Nipple biopsy | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Referral to dermatology | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Case of paget disease. As always, the next step after imaging is core needle biopsy. Confined to the** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
