  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it's simple, just aspirate and celebrate!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Aspiration. For a 26-year-old female with a tender breast lump identified as a simple cyst on ultrasound, aspiration is the best management as it is both diagnostic and therapeutic, providing immediate relief and confirmation of benignity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSimple breast cysts are benign, fluid-filled sacs. Aspiration involves using a fine needle to withdraw the fluid, which typically appears clear or straw-colored. This procedure confirms the diagnosis of a simple cyst, alleviates the patient's discomfort by decompressing the lump, and provides reassurance. Given the patient's young age, lack of family history, and the clear ultrasound findings of a simple cyst, a conservative and minimally invasive approach like aspiration is highly appropriate, avoiding unnecessary surgical intervention or further complex imaging.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (MRI) (Incorrect): MRI is not indicated for a simple breast cyst. It is reserved for high-risk screening, cancer staging, or further evaluation of complex or indeterminate lesions.\nOption C (Excision) (Incorrect): Excision is an invasive surgical procedure and is overtreatment for a simple, benign cyst. It is reserved for suspicious solid masses or complex cysts that persist or show concerning features after aspiration or biopsy.\nOption D (Antibiotics) (Incorrect): Antibiotics are used to treat infections (e.g., mastitis, abscess). A simple cyst is a sterile, fluid-filled structure and does not require antibiotic treatment unless there are signs of infection, which are not present here.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Breast Lump Type | US Findings | Management |\n| :--------------- | :---------- | :--------- |\n| Simple Cyst      | Anechoic, smooth walls, posterior enhancement | Aspiration (diagnostic & therapeutic) |\n| Complex Cyst     | Internal echoes, thick walls, septations | Aspiration, +/- biopsy, close follow-up |\n| Solid Mass (Benign) | Fibroadenoma: oval, well-circumscribed | Observation, +/- core biopsy |\n| Solid Mass (Suspicious) | Irregular shape, spiculated margins, microcalcifications | Core needle biopsy, surgical excision |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Simple breast cysts in young women are aspirated, not excised.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a simple breast cyst appears as a well-circumscribed, anechoic (black) lesion with smooth, thin walls and posterior acoustic enhancement, indicating its fluid-filled nature.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) BI-RADS Atlas (2013) recommends BI-RADS 2 (benign) for simple cysts, indicating no further action or follow-up is needed beyond aspiration for symptomatic relief.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Aspirate | ✅ Correct |\n| B | MRI | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Excision | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Antibiotics | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) We aspirate breast masses only in a case of cyst.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
