  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Omentum out? Get the patient in!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Laparotomy. The presence of exposed omentum unequivocally indicates fascial penetration and peritoneal breach, necessitating surgical exploration regardless of hemodynamic stability or negative CT findings.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nStab wounds with omental evisceration are a clear indication for mandatory surgical exploration. This signifies a breach of the peritoneum, and even if the patient is hemodynamically stable and initial imaging is negative, there is a high risk of underlying bowel or other visceral injury that could lead to delayed peritonitis, sepsis, and significant morbidity if not addressed promptly. Prompt exploration allows for identification and repair of these potentially life-threatening injuries.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Observation is inappropriate because exposed omentum is a definitive sign of peritoneal violation, requiring surgical exploration to rule out or repair internal injuries.\nOption B (Incorrect): Closing the wound without exploration would trap potential contamination and miss significant intra-abdominal injuries, leading to delayed complications.\nOption C (Incorrect): Leaving the wound open without exploration is also insufficient, as it fails to address the underlying peritoneal breach and potential visceral damage.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Finding | Management | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Hemodynamically unstable stab wound | Immediate Laparotomy | Life-threatening hemorrhage/injury |\n| Stab wound with omental evisceration (stable) | Mandatory Laparotomy | Peritoneal breach, high risk of missed injury |\n| Stab wound, no evisceration, stable, no signs of peritonitis | Local wound exploration, DPL, or serial exams/CT | Rule out fascial penetration/intra-abdominal injury |\n| Superficial stab wound (no fascial penetration) | Local wound care | No risk of intra-abdominal injury |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Omental evisceration in a stab wound means mandatory laparotomy, always.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile the CT was negative in this case, intraoperatively, the surgeon would identify the fascial defect, inspect the omentum for injury, and systematically explore the abdominal cavity for bowel, mesenteric, or solid organ damage, which could be missed by imaging alone.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) guidelines, 11th Edition (2022). ATLS recommends mandatory laparotomy for evisceration.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Observation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Close the wound | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Leave the wound open | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Laparotomy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Omentum was seen, so go for laparotomy even if the patient is hemodynamically stable.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
