  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When FAST fails, DPL prevails for unstable blunt trauma.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient presents with hemodynamic instability following blunt abdominal trauma and is unresponsive to fluid resuscitation. Despite a negative FAST exam, the patient's instability mandates further investigation for intra-abdominal hemorrhage or injury. In this critical scenario, Diagnostic Peritoneal Lavage (DPL) is the appropriate next step.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDPL is a highly sensitive diagnostic tool for detecting intra-abdominal injury, particularly hemorrhage, in the setting of blunt abdominal trauma. It involves inserting a catheter into the peritoneal cavity and aspirating fluid; if no gross blood is aspirated, saline is infused and then drained. The presence of red blood cells, white blood cells, or other contents (e.g., bile, enteric contents) above specific thresholds indicates a positive result, necessitating surgical exploration. Its utility shines when a patient is too unstable for CT and FAST is not definitive enough to rule out significant injury in an unstable patient.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Laparotomy) (Incorrect): While laparotomy might ultimately be needed, it's premature without a clear indication of intra-abdominal injury, especially after a negative FAST. DPL helps confirm the need for surgery.\nOption B (CT scan) (Incorrect): The patient is hypotensive and not responding to fluids, indicating hemodynamic instability. An unstable patient should not be taken to CT scan, as it delays definitive treatment and risks decompensation outside the operating room.\nOption D (FAST) (Incorrect): A FAST exam has already been performed and was negative. While FAST is a good initial screening tool, its sensitivity for certain injuries (e.g., bowel, solid organ injury without free fluid) is limited, and a negative result in an unstable patient necessitates further investigation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Indication | Pros | Cons |\n| :------- | :--------- | :--- | :--- |\n| FAST | Initial screen for free fluid in trauma | Rapid, non-invasive, repeatable, bedside | Operator dependent, poor for retroperitoneal/bowel injury, limited sensitivity |\n| DPL | Unstable trauma, negative/equivocal FAST | Highly sensitive for hemorrhage, rapid | Invasive, risk of iatrogenic injury, cannot localize injury |\n| CT Scan | Hemodynamically stable trauma | High sensitivity/specificity, localizes injury, detects retroperitoneal injury | Requires stable patient, radiation exposure, contrast risk, time-consuming |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unstable blunt trauma + negative FAST = DPL.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA positive DPL is indicated by gross blood aspiration (>10 mL), or if lavage fluid contains >100,000 RBCs/mm³, >500 WBCs/mm³, bile, or enteric contents.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nATLS (Advanced Trauma Life Support) Guidelines, 10th Edition (2018). ATLS recommends DPL for unstable blunt abdominal trauma patients with equivocal or negative FAST exams.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Laparotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CT scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | DPL | ✅ Correct |\n| D | FAST | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Blunt trauma + unstable so we did FAST first, but since it’s negative we go for DPL this time.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
