  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let pregnancy mask the most common surgical culprit!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is appendicitis. Despite the non-specific right-sided abdominal pain in a 16-week pregnant patient, appendicitis remains the most common non-obstetric surgical emergency during pregnancy, making it the most likely diagnosis for acute abdominal pain.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAppendicitis occurs in approximately 1 in 1,500 pregnancies, making it the leading cause of acute abdominal pain requiring surgical intervention. The diagnosis can be challenging due to the physiological changes of pregnancy, including the upward and lateral displacement of the appendix by the gravid uterus, which can alter the typical pain presentation. Furthermore, physiological leukocytosis and common pregnancy symptoms like nausea and vomiting can mimic appendicitis, complicating the clinical picture. Early diagnosis and intervention are crucial to prevent perforation and adverse maternal-fetal outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (gastritis) (Incorrect): While possible, gastritis typically presents with epigastric pain and is rarely a surgical emergency. It is not the most common cause of acute abdominal pain requiring intervention in pregnancy.\nOption B (pancreatitis) (Incorrect): Pancreatitis can occur in pregnancy, often related to gallstones, but it is less common than appendicitis and typically presents with severe epigastric pain radiating to the back.\nOption C (cholecystitis) (Incorrect): Cholecystitis is also common in pregnancy due to hormonal changes affecting bile composition and gallbladder motility, usually presenting with right upper quadrant pain. However, appendicitis still holds the title for the most common non-obstetric surgical emergency.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Incidence in Pregnancy | Typical Pain Location | Key Diagnostic Challenge |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Appendicitis | 1 in 1,500 | Variable (often RLQ, but can shift) | Atypical presentation due to uterine displacement; physiological leukocytosis |\n| Cholecystitis | 1 in 1,000-10,000 | RUQ | Shares symptoms like nausea/vomiting with pregnancy |\n| Pancreatitis | 1 in 1,000-10,000 | Epigastric, radiating to back | Elevated amylase/lipase can be seen in normal pregnancy, but usually not to diagnostic levels |\n| Gastritis | Common | Epigastric | Usually managed medically, not a surgical emergency |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: When in doubt about acute abdominal pain in pregnancy, think appendicitis first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound is the initial imaging modality of choice for appendicitis in pregnancy, often followed by MRI if ultrasound is inconclusive. In the operating room, the appendix may be found in an atypical location due to uterine displacement, requiring a thorough exploration.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 212 (2019) on Appendicitis in Pregnancy recommends early diagnosis and surgical intervention to minimize maternal and fetal morbidity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | gastritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | pancreatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | cholecystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | appendicitis | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) They did not specify the location, but the most common cause is appendicitis.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
