  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Rovsing's: Push left, pain right. Don't get it wrong!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question describes a sign related to appendicitis. While the description in the question is inverted, the intended answer is Rovsing's sign, which is characterized by pain in the right lower quadrant (RLQ) when the left lower quadrant (LLQ) is palpated. This referred pain is a classic indicator of peritoneal irritation due to an inflamed appendix.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRovsing's sign is a manifestation of referred pain caused by the irritation of the parietal peritoneum in the right lower quadrant. When the left lower quadrant is palpated, it increases pressure within the colon, which then transmits this pressure across the abdomen, distending the cecum and irritating the inflamed peritoneum surrounding the appendix. This mechanical irritation elicits pain in the RLQ, even though the primary palpation occurs on the contralateral side.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Psoas sign is pain on passive extension of the right hip or active flexion of the right hip against resistance, indicating a retrocecal appendix.\nOption C (Incorrect): Obturator sign is pain on passive internal rotation of the flexed right hip, indicating a pelvic appendix.\nOption D (Incorrect): Blumberg sign refers to rebound tenderness, which is pain upon release of deep palpation, indicating general peritoneal irritation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Sign | Description | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Rovsing's | RLQ pain with LLQ palpation | Peritoneal irritation from inflamed appendix |\n| Psoas | RLQ pain with right hip extension | Retrocecal appendix |\n| Obturator | RLQ pain with right hip internal rotation | Pelvic appendix |\n| Blumberg's | Rebound tenderness | General peritoneal inflammation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Rovsing's: LLQ palpation, RLQ pain. Psoas: hip extension. Obturator: hip rotation. Blumberg: rebound.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, an inflamed appendix appears as a dilated, non-compressible tubular structure (>6mm diameter) with wall thickening, periappendiceal fat stranding, and sometimes an appendicolith. Intraoperatively, the appendix will be erythematous, edematous, and potentially purulent or gangrenous.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nACR Appropriateness Criteria for Acute Appendicitis (2021): Recommends CT with IV contrast for adults and US for children and pregnant women as initial imaging modalities.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Psoas | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Rovsing | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Obturator | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Blumberg | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) Bad recall. Palpating the LLQ causes RLQ pain.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
