  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 A normal appendix means the real culprit is still hiding!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, \"Look for Meckel's diverticulum.\" This is a critical intraoperative decision when the appendix appears normal despite strong clinical suspicion for appendicitis, as other pathologies must be ruled out before concluding the operation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMeckel's diverticulum is the most common congenital anomaly of the gastrointestinal tract, a remnant of the omphalomesenteric duct. It can become inflamed, mimicking acute appendicitis, a condition known as Meckel's diverticulitis. The classic 'rule of 2s' (2% of population, 2 feet from ileocecal valve, 2 inches long, 2 types of ectopic tissue, symptomatic by age 2) highlights its prevalence and characteristics. Intraoperatively, if the appendix is found to be normal, a systematic search for a Meckel's diverticulum along the ileum is mandatory to identify the true source of the patient's symptoms and prevent a missed diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Removing a normal appendix (negative appendectomy) is unnecessary, adds surgical morbidity, and fails to address the underlying cause of the patient's symptoms.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"Do open surgery and explore\" is too vague. The current approach is already exploratory (laparoscopic or open). The key is *what* specifically to explore for, which is Meckel's diverticulum in this context.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"Cl\" is incomplete, but if it implies closing, closing without identifying the pathology after a negative appendectomy is considered malpractice and leaves the patient's problem unresolved.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Presentation | Intraoperative Finding (if appendix normal) | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Acute Appendicitis | RLQ pain, rigidity, tenderness | Inflamed appendix | Appendectomy |\n| Meckel's Diverticulitis | Mimics appendicitis, GI bleeding | Inflamed Meckel's diverticulum | Diverticulectomy |\n| Mesenteric Adenitis | RLQ pain, fever, diffuse tenderness | Enlarged mesenteric lymph nodes | Conservative, observation |\n| Ovarian Torsion/PID | RLQ/pelvic pain, often female | Twisted ovary/inflamed adnexa | Detorsion/antibiotics |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Normal appendix + RLQ pain = search for Meckel's diverticulum.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, if the appendix appears normal, the surgeon should systematically trace the small bowel proximally from the ileocecal junction for approximately 80-100 cm (2 feet) to identify a Meckel's diverticulum, which typically appears as a blind-ending pouch on the antimesenteric border of the ileum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES 2020 Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis: These guidelines emphasize the importance of thorough exploration for alternative diagnoses if the appendix is found to be normal during appendectomy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Remove the appendix and close | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Look for meckles diverticulum | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Do open surgery and explore | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cl | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
