  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just remove the appendix; find the real culprit!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, which involves performing the appendectomy and referring the patient to gastroenterology. This approach addresses both the initial surgical indication and the unexpected finding of inflamed cecum and terminal ileum, which strongly suggests inflammatory bowel disease (IBD).\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWhen a patient presents with symptoms suggestive of acute appendicitis but a normal appendix is found intraoperatively, the surgeon must systematically inspect the surrounding structures for alternative pathology. The discovery of an inflamed cecum and terminal ileum is a critical finding, often indicative of Crohn's disease or other forms of enterocolitis. While the appendix itself is not inflamed, performing the appendectomy is often still done to prevent future diagnostic confusion. The most crucial step is to ensure the patient receives appropriate follow-up and diagnostic workup for the underlying condition, which is best managed by a gastroenterologist.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Right hemicolectomy) (Incorrect): This is an overly aggressive and unnecessary procedure for an undiagnosed inflammatory condition. It would be performed only for severe, complicated IBD or malignancy, not for initial presentation.\nOption B (Close without further intervention) (Incorrect): This is negligent. Ignoring inflamed cecum and terminal ileum would miss a significant underlying pathology that requires diagnosis and treatment.\nOption D (Take biopsy of cecum and terminal ileum) (Incorrect): While biopsies are part of the diagnostic process for IBD, simply taking biopsies without a plan for comprehensive follow-up and management by a specialist is incomplete. The referral to gastroenterology (Option C) encompasses the entire diagnostic and treatment pathway, including biopsies.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Finding in OR | Likely Diagnosis | Best Next Step (Surgical) | Best Next Step (Medical) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Normal appendix, inflamed cecum/terminal ileum | Inflammatory Bowel Disease (e.g., Crohn's) | Appendectomy (often) | Refer to Gastroenterology |\n| Normal appendix, mesenteric adenitis | Viral/Bacterial infection | Appendectomy (often) | Symptomatic treatment, observation |\n| Normal appendix, ovarian pathology | Gynecological issue | Address pathology (if indicated) | Refer to Gynecology |\n| Perforated appendix | Acute Appendicitis | Appendectomy, lavage | Antibiotics, drainage (if abscess) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Normal appendix + inflamed ileum/cecum = IBD until proven otherwise. Refer to GI.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the appendix would appear pink, supple, and non-edematous. The cecum and terminal ileum, however, would show signs of inflammation such as erythema, edema, and possibly thickening of the bowel wall. Mesenteric lymphadenopathy might also be present. Pre-operative CT scan might have shown thickening of the terminal ileum or cecum, possibly with mesenteric fat stranding, even if the appendix appeared normal.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guidelines for the Management of Crohn's Disease (2018) recommends endoscopy with biopsies for diagnosis and characterization of IBD.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Right hemicolectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Close without further intervention | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Appendectomy and refer the patient to gastroenterology | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Take biopsy of cecum and terminal ileum | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Refer the patient to gastroenterology as it’s a case of IBD. The other choices don't make sense.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
