  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When K is low, the heart's a no-go without an ECG!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, ECG. In a post-operative patient with paralytic ileus and hypokalemia, the immediate priority is to assess for life-threatening cardiac complications, which an ECG can rapidly identify.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHypokalemia, defined as serum potassium <3.5 mEq/L, significantly impacts cardiac electrophysiology by altering the resting membrane potential and repolarization. This can lead to characteristic ECG changes such as T-wave flattening or inversion, prominent U waves, ST-segment depression, and prolonged QT intervals. These changes predispose patients to dangerous ventricular arrhythmias, including torsades de pointes, making immediate cardiac assessment via ECG crucial for patient safety and guiding urgent potassium repletion.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Urine osmolarity) (Incorrect): While urine osmolarity can be useful in assessing fluid balance or kidney function, it does not directly evaluate the immediate life-threatening consequences of hypokalemia.\nOption B (Urine K) (Incorrect): Measuring urine potassium is valuable for determining the etiology of hypokalemia (renal vs. extrarenal losses) but is not the best *initial* investigation when cardiac stability is paramount. It helps guide long-term management, not immediate risk assessment.\nOption C (Stool K) (Incorrect): Stool potassium measurement is rarely a primary investigation for hypokalemia, especially in a post-operative setting with paralytic ileus. While GI losses can cause hypokalemia, direct stool K measurement is not a standard first-line diagnostic tool.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Investigation | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| ECG | Assess cardiac rhythm and repolarization abnormalities, immediate risk stratification for arrhythmias |\n| Serum Potassium | Confirm diagnosis, quantify severity, monitor treatment |\n| Urine Potassium | Differentiate renal vs. extrarenal potassium loss, guide specific management strategies |\n| Arterial Blood Gas (ABG) | Assess acid-base status, as hypokalemia often coexists with acid-base disturbances |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hypokalemia? Think heart first, get an ECG.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nAn ECG in hypokalemia may show T-wave flattening or inversion, prominent U waves, ST-segment depression, and prolonged QT intervals, indicating increased risk for arrhythmias.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe European Society of Cardiology (ESC) 2022 Guidelines for the management of patients with ventricular arrhythmias and the prevention of sudden cardiac death recommend prompt correction of electrolyte imbalances, including hypokalemia, to prevent life-threatening arrhythmias.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Urine osmolarity | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Urine K | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Stool K | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | ECG | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Hypokalemia? Go for an ECG because of the effect it has on the heart.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
