  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the NG tube shows red, scope the upper GI instead!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Upper GI endoscopy. The presence of fresh blood and coffee ground aspirate from the NG tube is highly indicative of an upper gastrointestinal bleed, for which endoscopy is the gold standard for diagnosis and often treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUpper GI endoscopy allows for direct visualization of the esophageal, gastric, and duodenal mucosa, enabling precise identification of the bleeding source such as ulcers, varices, or Mallory-Weiss tears. Beyond diagnosis, it offers immediate therapeutic interventions like injection therapy, cauterization, clipping, or banding, which can effectively control acute bleeding and prevent re-bleeding. This direct, real-time assessment and intervention capability makes it superior to imaging for active UGIB.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Abdominal CT is excellent for evaluating intra-abdominal pathology like anastomotic leaks, abscesses, or obstruction post-surgery, but it is not the primary diagnostic tool for active upper GI bleeding. While CT angiography can detect active bleeding, it lacks the therapeutic capabilities and direct visualization of endoscopy, making it a secondary choice for this presentation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Primary Use | Advantages | Limitations |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Upper GI Endoscopy | UGIB diagnosis & treatment | Direct visualization, therapeutic intervention, high sensitivity/specificity | Invasive, requires sedation, limited to upper GI |\n| Colonoscopy | LGIB diagnosis & treatment | Direct visualization, therapeutic intervention, high sensitivity/specificity | Invasive, requires bowel prep, limited to lower GI |\n| CT Angiography | Active GI bleeding (obscure/massive) | Non-invasive, can localize bleeding source, useful when endoscopy fails | Radiation exposure, less sensitive for slow bleeds, no therapeutic capability |\n| Capsule Endoscopy | Obscure GI bleeding | Non-invasive, visualizes small bowel | No therapeutic capability, cannot control movement, limited for acute bleeding |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: NG aspirate with blood = scope the upper GI first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn upper GI endoscopy, one would directly visualize the source of bleeding, such as an actively bleeding gastric ulcer with visible vessel, oozing duodenal ulcer, or esophageal varices. The appearance of fresh blood or coffee grounds in the stomach would also be evident.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Patients with Acute Upper Gastrointestinal Bleeding (2021). It recommends urgent upper endoscopy within 24 hours for most patients with acute UGIB.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Upper GI endoscopy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Abdominal CT | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
