  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 NSAIDs are a pain in the gut, sometimes a hole in the gut!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct diagnosis is Perforated peptic ulcer. This patient's presentation of sudden, severe epigastric pain, tenderness, and rigidity, especially in the context of NSAID use, is highly classic for a perforated peptic ulcer, which leads to chemical peritonitis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNSAIDs inhibit cyclooxygenase (COX) enzymes, reducing prostaglandin synthesis, which is crucial for gastric mucosal protection. This predisposes to peptic ulcer disease (PUD). When an ulcer erodes through the gastric or duodenal wall, it causes a perforation, leading to the spillage of gastric or duodenal contents into the peritoneal cavity. This spillage results in acute chemical peritonitis, manifesting as sudden, excruciating abdominal pain, often localized to the epigastrium initially, followed by diffuse tenderness and characteristic 'board-like' rigidity on examination due to involuntary guarding of the abdominal muscles. This clinical picture demands immediate surgical intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Esophagitis) (Incorrect): Esophagitis typically presents with burning retrosternal pain, dysphagia, or odynophagia, not sudden severe epigastric pain with peritoneal signs like rigidity.\nOption B (Acute gastritis) (Incorrect): Acute gastritis causes epigastric pain, nausea, and sometimes vomiting, but it rarely presents with the sudden, severe pain and board-like rigidity indicative of peritonitis.\nOption D (Boerhaave syndrome) (Incorrect): Boerhaave syndrome is an esophageal rupture, usually following forceful vomiting, presenting with severe chest pain, dyspnea, and often subcutaneous emphysema. While severe, the patient denied vomiting, and the pain is primarily epigastric with rigidity, making perforation more likely.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Perforated Peptic Ulcer | Acute Gastritis | Esophagitis | Boerhaave Syndrome |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Onset of Pain** | Sudden, severe | Gradual to acute | Gradual, burning | Sudden, severe |\n| **Pain Location** | Epigastric, then diffuse | Epigastric | Retrosternal | Chest, epigastric |\n| **Associated Symptoms** | Nausea, rigidity, tenderness | Nausea, dyspepsia | Dysphagia, odynophagia | Vomiting (often preceding), dyspnea, subcutaneous emphysema |\n| **Risk Factors** | NSAIDs, H. pylori, smoking | NSAIDs, alcohol, stress | GERD, infection | Forceful vomiting |\n| **Physical Exam** | Board-like rigidity, tenderness | Epigastric tenderness | Normal or mild tenderness | Crepitus, tenderness |\n| **Key Diagnostic** | Free air on imaging | Endoscopy | Endoscopy | CT chest with contrast |\n| **Treatment** | Surgical repair | PPIs, H2 blockers | PPIs, lifestyle changes | Surgical repair, drainage |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: NSAID use + sudden severe abdominal pain + rigidity = perforated ulcer until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, an upright chest X-ray or abdominal X-ray will often show free air under the diaphragm (pneumoperitoneum). A CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis is more sensitive for detecting free air and identifying the site of perforation. Intraoperatively, one would observe gastric or duodenal contents in the peritoneal cavity and a visible perforation, typically on the anterior wall of the duodenum or stomach.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Peptic Ulcer Disease (2017) recommends prompt diagnosis and surgical intervention for perforated ulcers.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Esophagitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Acute gastritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Perforated peptic ulcer | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Boerhaave syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) History of NSAID use is classic for PUD.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
