  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't wait too long, but don't start too soon; 8-10 years is the UC sweet spot.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 8-10 years after diagnosis. This timing is crucial for initiating colon cancer surveillance in patients with Ulcerative Colitis due to the increased risk of colorectal cancer associated with chronic inflammation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic inflammation in Ulcerative Colitis leads to a significantly elevated risk of colorectal cancer, particularly in patients with extensive disease. The risk begins to rise substantially after 8-10 years of disease duration. Surveillance colonoscopies are performed to detect dysplasia or early-stage cancer, which can be managed endoscopically or surgically, thereby improving patient outcomes. The 8-10 year mark allows for the accumulation of sufficient inflammatory burden to increase cancer risk, while still providing an opportunity for early detection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Annually till age of 50 is not the standard surveillance protocol for UC-associated cancer. Surveillance frequency is based on risk factors (duration, extent, inflammation severity, primary sclerosing cholangitis), not a fixed age.\nOption B (Incorrect): Surveillance is indicated regardless of the current inflammatory state, as the cumulative inflammatory burden over time is the primary driver of cancer risk. Even patients in remission still require surveillance.\nOption C (Incorrect): While a baseline colonoscopy at diagnosis is often performed to assess disease extent and exclude pre-existing dysplasia, regular surveillance for cancer risk typically commences after a period of disease duration, usually 8-10 years.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Screening/Surveillance Start | Frequency |\n|---|---|---|\n| Average Risk Colon Cancer | Age 45 (USPSTF) or 50 (AGA) | Every 10 years (colonoscopy) |\n| Ulcerative Colitis (extensive) | 8-10 years after diagnosis | Annually to every 3 years |\n| Familial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP) | Puberty (10-12 years) | Annually |\n| Lynch Syndrome | Age 20-25 or 2-5 years before earliest CRC in family | Every 1-2 years |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: UC cancer surveillance starts 8-10 years post-diagnosis for extensive disease.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring surveillance colonoscopy, look for subtle mucosal changes such as flat or raised dysplastic lesions, strictures, or mass lesions. Biopsies should be taken from any suspicious areas, and often random biopsies are also performed, especially in areas of chronic inflammation, to detect microscopic dysplasia. Chromoendoscopy can enhance detection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Colorectal Cancer Screening 2021 recommends surveillance colonoscopy 8 years after diagnosis in patients with extensive UC. American Gastroenterological Association (AGA) guidelines also support this timing.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Annually till age of 50 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | If there is mild inflammation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | At time of diagnosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 8-10 years after diagnosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
