  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't be a colon-oscopy slacker, follow those polyps back!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, repeat colonoscopy in 3 years. This interval is appropriate for a 43-year-old male with a family history of colon cancer who had a completely removed tubular adenoma, balancing surveillance efficacy with patient burden.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nColorectal cancer screening and surveillance protocols are based on the adenoma-carcinoma sequence, where most colorectal cancers arise from adenomatous polyps. The surveillance interval after polypectomy is determined by the number, size, and histology of the removed polyps, as well as patient risk factors like family history. A tubular adenoma, even if completely removed, indicates a propensity for polyp formation, and the patient's age and family history further elevate their risk, necessitating a shorter surveillance interval than for low-risk individuals.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (3-6 month) (Incorrect): This interval is typically reserved for incomplete resections, piecemeal resections of large polyps, or high-risk features requiring early re-evaluation, not for a completely removed tubular adenoma.\nOption C (5 years) (Incorrect): A 5-year interval is generally recommended for low-risk findings, such as 1-2 small tubular adenomas (<10mm) in patients without significant family history, which is not the case here.\nOption D (no need) (Incorrect): Surveillance is always indicated after adenoma removal to detect metachronous polyps and prevent colorectal cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Polyp Type/Risk Factor | Surveillance Interval | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1-2 small tubular adenomas (<10mm) | 5-10 years | Low risk of advanced neoplasia |\n| 3-10 adenomas OR any adenoma >10mm OR high-grade dysplasia OR villous features | 3 years | Increased risk of advanced neoplasia |\n| >10 adenomas | <3 years (often 1 year) | High risk, consider genetic syndromes |\n| Sessile serrated polyp (SSP) <10mm without dysplasia | 5 years | Intermediate risk |\n| SSP >10mm or with dysplasia | 3 years | Higher risk |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Family history + adenoma = shorter surveillance interval.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopically, a tubular adenoma typically appears as a pedunculated or sessile polyp with a smooth or slightly lobulated surface, often reddish compared to the surrounding mucosa. Complete removal is confirmed by visual inspection of the polypectomy site.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American College of Gastroenterology (ACG) 2020 guidelines for colorectal cancer screening and surveillance recommend a 3-year surveillance colonoscopy for patients with 3-10 adenomas, or any adenoma >10mm, or adenoma with high-grade dysplasia or villous features. While this patient only had one tubular adenoma, the family history and age often push towards a more aggressive surveillance, making 3 years a reasonable interval.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 3-6 month | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 3years | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 5 years | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | no need | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Repeat colonoscopy in 3 years.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
