  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Villous polyps are the silent assassins of the colon.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Villous. Villous adenomas are characterized by their extensive finger-like projections and higher proportion of dysplastic epithelium, which directly correlates with an increased risk of malignant transformation compared to other adenomatous polyps.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nVillous adenomas are distinguished by their frond-like, finger-like projections that extend from the mucosal surface, often comprising >80% of the polyp's architecture. This extensive villous component provides a larger surface area for dysplastic change and is associated with a higher degree of cellular atypia and increased rates of high-grade dysplasia and invasive carcinoma. Their sessile nature and larger size also contribute to their elevated malignant potential.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Tubular adenomas are the most common type, characterized by a glandular, tubular architecture. They have the lowest malignant potential among adenomatous polyps due to a smaller proportion of dysplastic epithelium.\nOption C (Incorrect): Tubulovillous adenomas exhibit a mixed architecture, containing both tubular and villous components, with the villous component typically comprising 20-80%. Their malignant potential is intermediate, falling between tubular and villous adenomas.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Polyp Type | Malignant Potential | Histology |\n|---|---|---|\n| Villous Adenoma | Highest | >80% villous architecture (finger-like projections) |\n| Tubulovillous Adenoma | Intermediate | 20-80% villous architecture |\n| Tubular Adenoma | Lowest | <20% villous architecture (glandular/tubular) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Villous polyps are villainous; they have the highest cancer risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn colonoscopy, villous adenomas often appear as broad-based, sessile, velvety, or cauliflower-like lesions, frequently larger than other polyp types.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guidelines for Colorectal Cancer Screening and Surveillance (2021) recommend surveillance intervals based on polyp histology and number, with villous features influencing shorter intervals.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Villous | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Tubular | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Tubulovillous | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
