  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Obstructed colon? Cut it out, stat!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient presents with large intestinal obstruction due to a biopsy-proven sigmoid adenocarcinoma. In this acute setting, the immediate priority is to relieve the obstruction and address the tumor. Therefore, sigmoidectomy is the most appropriate next step.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAn obstructing colorectal cancer is a surgical emergency. While comprehensive staging is crucial for non-obstructing lesions, the presence of obstruction dictates a primary surgical approach to alleviate symptoms, prevent complications like perforation, and remove the tumor. This often involves a resective procedure, sometimes with a diverting ostomy, depending on the patient's clinical stability and the surgeon's judgment. The goal is to restore bowel patency and manage the cancer.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Colonoscopy is contraindicated in complete large bowel obstruction due to the high risk of perforation and the inability to fully evaluate the colon beyond the obstruction. It would be appropriate for a non-obstructing mass for full colon evaluation.\nOption B (Incorrect): CT abdomen is essential for staging but is not the *best next step* when an acute obstruction is present and the diagnosis is confirmed. Surgery takes precedence to relieve the obstruction.\nOption C (Incorrect): MRI pelvis is primarily used for local staging of rectal cancer, not typically for sigmoid colon cancer, and certainly not as the immediate next step for an obstructing lesion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Scenario | Best Next Step | Rationale |\n| :---------------- | :------------- | :-------- |\n| Obstructing CRC | Surgery (e.g., Sigmoidectomy) | Relieve obstruction, prevent perforation, address tumor |\n| Non-obstructing CRC (biopsy confirmed) | Staging (CT chest/abdomen/pelvis), then elective surgery | Assess extent of disease, plan definitive treatment |\n| Suspected CRC (no obstruction, no biopsy) | Colonoscopy with biopsy | Confirm diagnosis, evaluate entire colon |\n| Rectal cancer | MRI pelvis for local staging | Assess depth of invasion, nodal involvement for neoadjuvant therapy planning |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Obstruction trumps staging. Operate first!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, you would typically see dilated proximal colon with a clear transition point at the sigmoid mass, indicating the obstruction. Intraoperatively, the sigmoid colon proximal to the tumor would be significantly distended and potentially edematous.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colon Cancer (2023). They recommend surgical resection for obstructing colon cancer, often as an emergency procedure.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Colonoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CT abdomen | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | MRI pelvis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Sigmoidectomy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) A case of large obstruction, hence why we need to go for surgery first. If the patient is not curren** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
