  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't ignore new bowel changes; always scope the sigmoid!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nSigmoid cancer is the most appropriate diagnosis given the patient's age, change in bowel habits, and specific bleeding pattern without rectal fullness. This constellation of symptoms is highly suggestive of a left-sided colorectal malignancy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSigmoid colon cancers often present with altered bowel habits (constipation or alternating with diarrhea) due to partial luminal obstruction. The streaking of blood in the stool occurs as feces pass over the friable tumor surface. The absence of rectal fullness helps localize the lesion proximal to the palpable rectum, making the sigmoid colon a prime suspect.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Rectal cancer would typically cause rectal fullness or tenesmus, which is explicitly absent here. While some high rectal cancers might not be palpable, the sigmoid is a more direct fit for \"no fullness.\"\nOption C (Incorrect): Chronic hemorrhoids are common but do not explain the \"constipation on and off\" as a new change in bowel habits in an old patient, which is a red flag for malignancy. Hemorrhoidal bleeding is usually bright red and on the surface of the stool or toilet paper, not typically \"streaking in the stool\" from a higher source.\nOption D (Incorrect): Cecal cancer (right-sided) typically presents with iron deficiency anemia due to occult bleeding, or a palpable mass, and less commonly with gross streaking of blood or constipation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Symptom | Sigmoid Cancer | Rectal Cancer | Hemorrhoids | Cecal Cancer |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Age | Older | Older | Any | Older |\n| Bowel Habits | Constipation/alternating | Tenesmus, urgency, altered | Often normal, or straining | Anemia, diarrhea |\n| Bleeding | Streaking in stool, dark red | Bright/dark red, mixed with stool | Bright red, on stool/paper | Occult, anemia |\n| Rectal Fullness | No | Yes (often) | No | No |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: New onset constipation with streaking blood in an old patient without rectal fullness = sigmoid cancer until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nColonoscopy is the diagnostic gold standard, revealing an exophytic or circumferential mass in the sigmoid colon. CT scan would show a thickened sigmoid wall or pericolic fat stranding.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Cancer Society (ACS) Guidelines for Colorectal Cancer Screening and Surveillance (2023). Recommends screening for average-risk individuals starting at age 45, and earlier for those with risk factors or symptoms.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sigmoid cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | rectal cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | chronic hemorrhoid. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | cecal cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
