  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Jaundice + RUQ pain = Ultrasound first, always.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct initial step for an obese patient presenting with jaundice, abdominal pain, and RUQ tenderness is an abdominal ultrasound. This presentation strongly suggests biliary obstruction, likely due to choledocholithiasis, and ultrasound is the most appropriate first-line imaging modality.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAbdominal ultrasound is the preferred initial diagnostic tool for suspected biliary obstruction because it is non-invasive, readily available, relatively inexpensive, and does not involve radiation. It is highly effective in detecting gallstones, assessing common bile duct dilation, and identifying the presence of cholecystitis or other causes of obstruction. Its ability to visualize the gallbladder and biliary tree makes it superior to other initial tests for this clinical scenario.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (MRCP) (Incorrect): While excellent for detailed visualization of the biliary tree, MRCP is typically reserved for cases where ultrasound findings are equivocal or for surgical planning, not as the initial diagnostic step due to cost and availability.\nOption C (CT) (Incorrect): CT scans are less sensitive than ultrasound for detecting gallstones and involve radiation. They are generally used if pancreatic pathology or malignancy is highly suspected, or if ultrasound is inconclusive, but not as the initial test for suspected choledocholithiasis.\nOption D (Biopsy) (Incorrect): Biopsy is an invasive procedure used for definitive tissue diagnosis, primarily for suspected malignancy. It is never an initial diagnostic step for obstructive jaundice without prior imaging to localize and characterize a potential mass.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Imaging Modality | Primary Use in Biliary Disease | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|------------------|-------------------------------|------------|---------------|\n| Abdominal US     | Initial evaluation of jaundice, gallstones, duct dilation | Non-invasive, no radiation, cost-effective, readily available | Operator dependent, limited view of distal CBD/pancreas |\n| CT Scan          | Pancreatic masses, complications of cholecystitis, staging | Good for solid organs, complications, malignancy | Radiation exposure, less sensitive for small stones |\n| MRCP             | Detailed visualization of biliary/pancreatic ducts, stones | No radiation, excellent soft tissue contrast | Costly, limited availability, not therapeutic |\n| ERCP             | Diagnostic and therapeutic for CBD stones, strictures | Can remove stones, stent strictures | Invasive, risk of pancreatitis, perforation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Abdominal US is the first-line imaging for suspected biliary obstruction.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn abdominal ultrasound, you would look for gallstones within the gallbladder, dilation of the common bile duct (typically >6-8mm), and potentially a stone impacted in the distal common bile duct. Signs of cholecystitis like gallbladder wall thickening or pericholecystic fluid might also be present.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Gallstones and Cholecystitis (2019) recommends abdominal ultrasound as the initial imaging modality for suspected gallstone disease and biliary obstruction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | MRCP | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Abdominal US | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CT | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
