  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the gallbladder's inflamed, get it out fast!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient presents with classic signs and symptoms of acute cholecystitis, including a positive sonographic Murphy's sign and ultrasound findings of inflammation. Given the early presentation (within hours), emergency laparoscopic cholecystectomy is the recommended treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute cholecystitis is inflammation of the gallbladder, typically caused by gallstone obstruction of the cystic duct. Early laparoscopic cholecystectomy, performed within 72 hours of symptom onset, is preferred as it reduces hospital stay, conversion rates to open surgery, and overall complications compared to delayed surgery. This approach leverages minimally invasive techniques for definitive treatment during the acute inflammatory phase.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Conservative treatment and interval cholecystectomy is reserved for patients presenting after 72 hours, those with severe comorbidities, or those who fail initial non-operative management. The patient's early presentation makes immediate surgical intervention appropriate.\nOption B (Incorrect): Insertion of percutaneous cholecystostomy tube is typically reserved for critically ill patients who are not surgical candidates, or as a temporizing measure for severe cholecystitis with sepsis, not for an otherwise healthy patient presenting early.\nOption D (Incorrect): Emergency open cholecystectomy is generally reserved for cases where laparoscopic approach is contraindicated, fails, or in severe complicated cases (e.g., gangrenous cholecystitis, perforation) where a laparoscopic approach is deemed unsafe or impossible. Laparoscopic approach is the gold standard.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Early Acute Cholecystitis (<72h) | Delayed Acute Cholecystitis (>72h) | Percutaneous Cholecystostomy |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Timing of Surgery** | Emergency/Early Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy | Conservative management then interval Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy (6-8 weeks) | Temporizing measure, often followed by interval cholecystectomy |\n| **Patient Status** | Generally stable, otherwise healthy | May have resolving inflammation, or severe local inflammation | Critically ill, high surgical risk, severe sepsis |\n| **Goal** | Definitive treatment, prevent complications | Allow inflammation to subside, then definitive treatment | Decompression, source control for high-risk patients |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Early acute cholecystitis = early lap chole.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound findings for acute cholecystitis include gallbladder wall thickening (>3mm), pericholecystic fluid, gallstones, and a positive sonographic Murphy's sign (pain with transducer pressure over the gallbladder). Intraoperatively, the gallbladder will appear inflamed, edematous, and potentially distended.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis recommend early laparoscopic cholecystectomy within 72 hours for Grade I (mild) and Grade II (moderate) acute cholecystitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Conservative treatment and interval cholecystectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Insertion of percutaneous cholecystestomy tube | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Emergency laparoscopic cholecystectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Emergency open cholecystectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) Classic case of cholecystitis. The patient presented in the first 72h (side = six?) so go for lap ch** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
