  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't observe symptoms, remove the source of pain!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient presents with classic symptoms of biliary colic (RUQ pain radiating to the scapula, nausea, vomiting) and ultrasound evidence of gallstones. The presence of a 5mm gallbladder polyp is an incidental finding that does not alter the primary management for symptomatic cholelithiasis. Laparoscopic cholecystectomy is the definitive treatment for symptomatic gallstones.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSymptomatic cholelithiasis, characterized by biliary colic, is a clear indication for cholecystectomy. The pain is typically postprandial, episodic, and often radiates to the right shoulder or scapula due to shared visceral innervation (phrenic nerve irritation). A gallbladder polyp of 5mm is generally considered low risk for malignancy, especially in the absence of other suspicious features. Its removal is part of the cholecystectomy performed for the symptomatic gallstones.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Observation) (Incorrect): Observation is reserved for asymptomatic gallstones. This patient is symptomatic with classic biliary colic, requiring intervention.\nOption C (Radical cholecystectomy) (Incorrect): Radical cholecystectomy is indicated for gallbladder cancer. A 5mm polyp is not an indication for such an aggressive procedure, especially without further workup or suspicious features.\nOption D (Repeat US after 3 months) (Incorrect): While repeat imaging might be considered for isolated asymptomatic polyps of certain sizes, it is inappropriate for a patient presenting with symptomatic gallstones. The symptoms necessitate definitive treatment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Symptomatic Cholelithiasis | Asymptomatic Cholelithiasis | Gallbladder Polyp (<10mm) | Gallbladder Polyp (>10mm or suspicious) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Symptoms | RUQ pain, nausea, vomiting, radiating pain | None | None | None (usually) |\n| US Findings | Stones, +/- wall thickening | Stones | Polyp | Polyp, +/- wall thickening, mass |\n| Management | Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy | Observation (unless high risk) | Observation (serial US) | Cholecystectomy (due to malignancy risk) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Symptomatic gallstones + polyp = Lap chole.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, gallstones appear as echogenic foci with posterior acoustic shadowing, typically mobile within the gallbladder lumen. A gallbladder polyp appears as a non-mobile, echogenic mural protrusion without shadowing. Intraoperatively, the gallbladder would appear inflamed or distended, and the polyp would be visible on the mucosal surface after opening the specimen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES 2010 Guidelines for the Clinical Application of Laparoscopic Biliary Surgery recommend cholecystectomy for symptomatic cholelithiasis. SAGES 2019 Guidelines for the Management of Gallbladder Polyps recommend cholecystectomy for polyps >10mm or those with suspicious features; however, symptomatic gallstones with an incidental polyp warrant cholecystectomy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lap chole. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Observation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Radical cholecystectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Repeat US after 3 months | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
