  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hilar obstruction: intrahepatic ducts dilate, gallbladder stays deflated.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Klatskin tumor. This diagnosis is strongly supported by the combination of jaundice, dilated intrahepatic ducts, and a shrunken gallbladder, which points to an obstruction at the hepatic duct confluence.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA Klatskin tumor, or hilar cholangiocarcinoma, is a malignancy arising at the bifurcation of the common hepatic duct. The obstruction occurs proximal to the cystic duct insertion, leading to the characteristic finding of dilated intrahepatic ducts while the gallbladder remains non-distended or shrunken. Jaundice is a primary symptom due to impaired bile flow, and the shrunken gallbladder differentiates it from more distal obstructions where the gallbladder would typically be distended (Courvoisier's sign).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Acute Cholecystitis typically presents with a distended gallbladder and inflammation, not a shrunken gallbladder with intrahepatic duct dilatation as the primary finding.\nOption B (Incorrect): A Gall Bladder Stone in the gallbladder itself would cause cholecystitis, not typically jaundice and intrahepatic duct dilatation unless it migrates to the CBD or causes Mirizzi syndrome.\nOption C (Incorrect): CBD Stone (Choledocholithiasis) would cause jaundice and intrahepatic duct dilatation, but the gallbladder would typically be distended (Courvoisier's sign) if healthy, not shrunken, as the obstruction is usually distal to the cystic duct.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Klatskin Tumor | CBD Stone | Acute Cholecystitis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Jaundice | Common, progressive | Common, fluctuating | Less common, usually secondary |\n| Intrahepatic Ducts | Dilated | Dilated | Normal (unless CBD stone) |\n| Gallbladder | Shrunken/Normal | Distended (Courvoisier's) | Distended, inflamed |\n| Obstruction Location | Hilar (proximal to cystic duct) | CBD (distal to cystic duct) | Cystic duct |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Shrunken gallbladder + dilated intrahepatic ducts = hilar obstruction.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, you would see marked dilatation of the intrahepatic bile ducts with an abrupt cutoff at the hepatic hilum, and a non-distended or atrophic gallbladder. Intraoperatively, a firm, often infiltrative mass would be found at the confluence of the right and left hepatic ducts.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Hepatobiliary Cancers (e.g., 2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, staging, and management of cholangiocarcinoma, including hilar types.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Acute Cholecystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gall Bladder Stone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CBD Stone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | klatskin tumor | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
