  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ampullary cancer: distal obstruction, diffuse dilatation, early jaundice.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Ampullary cancer. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the clinical presentation of obstructive jaundice (jaundice, dark urine, cholestatic labs) and weight loss in an elderly patient, combined with the crucial imaging finding of dilatation of both intrahepatic and extrahepatic bile ducts.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAmpullary cancer originates from the ampulla of Vater, a critical anatomical point where the common bile duct and pancreatic duct enter the duodenum. Its strategic location means that even small tumors can cause early and significant obstruction of the distal common bile duct. This distal obstruction leads to the characteristic dilatation of *both* the intrahepatic and extrahepatic biliary tree, a key differentiator from more proximal lesions. The associated weight loss and epigastric pain are common systemic symptoms of malignancy in this region.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Klatskin tumor) (Incorrect): Klatskin tumors are hilar cholangiocarcinomas that typically cause intrahepatic duct dilatation and often spare the distal common bile duct, making the finding of *both* intrahepatic and extrahepatic duct dilatation less typical for a pure Klatskin. \nOption B (Gallbladder cancer) (Incorrect): While gallbladder cancer can cause obstructive jaundice by invading the common hepatic or common bile duct, it is less common for it to present with this specific pattern of diffuse intra- and extrahepatic ductal dilatation as the primary obstructive mechanism compared to an ampullary lesion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Ampullary Cancer | Klatskin Tumor | Pancreatic Head Cancer |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Location | Ampulla of Vater | Hilar bile ducts | Head of pancreas |\n| Jaundice | Early, often intermittent | Early, progressive | Early, progressive |\n| Duct Dilatation | Intrahepatic & Extrahepatic | Primarily Intrahepatic & Proximal Extrahepatic | Intrahepatic & Extrahepatic |\n| Courvoisier's Sign | Often present | Absent | Often present |\n| Weight Loss | Common | Common | Common |\n| Stool Color | Pale (acholic) | Pale (acholic) | Pale (acholic) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Distal obstruction = both intra- and extrahepatic duct dilatation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (e.g., CT or MRCP), you would observe a dilated common bile duct and intrahepatic ducts, with a mass or stricture at the ampulla. Endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) would reveal a hypoechoic mass at the ampulla. During endoscopy, a friable, ulcerated, or fungating mass at the ampulla of Vater would be visible.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Hepatobiliary Cancers (2023). These guidelines recommend EUS with biopsy for diagnosis and staging of ampullary lesions, followed by surgical resection (Whipple procedure) for resectable disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Klatskin tumor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gall bladder cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ampullary cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
