  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Air in bile, stone in gut, obstruction's the rut.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The presence of air in the biliary system (pneumobilia) in a patient with a long history of gallstones is pathognomonic for a cholecystoenteric fistula, which is the underlying mechanism of gallstone ileus.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstone ileus is a rare complication of chronic cholelithiasis where a large gallstone erodes through the gallbladder wall into an adjacent loop of bowel, most commonly the duodenum, forming a cholecystoenteric fistula. This fistula allows intestinal gas to enter the biliary tree, causing pneumobilia. The dislodged gallstone then travels down the gastrointestinal tract, eventually causing mechanical obstruction, typically in the terminal ileum, due to its size. This sequence of events is crucial for understanding the diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Acute Cholecystitis) (Incorrect): While gallstones are present, acute cholecystitis itself does not typically cause air in the biliary system. Pneumobilia indicates a communication between the biliary system and the GI tract, which is not a feature of uncomplicated acute cholecystitis.\nOption C (Acute pancreatitis) (Incorrect): Acute pancreatitis is inflammation of the pancreas, often caused by gallstones, but it does not involve air in the biliary system. Pneumobilia is not a diagnostic feature of pancreatitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Gallstone Ileus | Acute Cholecystitis | Emphysematous Cholecystitis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Pathophysiology** | Cholecystoenteric fistula, stone migration, bowel obstruction | Cystic duct obstruction by stone, inflammation | Acute cholecystitis with gas-forming organisms |\n| **Key Imaging Sign** | Pneumobilia, ectopic gallstone, bowel obstruction (Rigler's triad) | Gallbladder wall thickening, pericholecystic fluid, distension | Gas in gallbladder lumen/wall |\n| **Air in Biliary System** | **Present (diagnostic)** | Absent | Absent (air typically within GB) |\n| **Bowel Obstruction** | Present | Absent | Absent |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pneumobilia + gallstones = Gallstone ileus until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT scan is preferred), the classic Rigler's triad for gallstone ileus includes pneumobilia, small bowel obstruction, and an ectopic gallstone. A cholecystoenteric fistula may also be visualized. Intraoperatively, a distended bowel proximal to the obstruction and a collapsed bowel distally, with a palpable gallstone, would be found.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe World Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) guidelines for the management of gallstone ileus (2018) provide recommendations for diagnosis and surgical treatment, emphasizing the importance of early recognition of the classic imaging findings.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gallstone ileus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Acute Cholecystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Acute pancreatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
