  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When air meets bile, CT finds the stone that causes the pile!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Abdominal CT. This patient's presentation of obstruction with pneumobilia strongly suggests gallstone ileus, for which CT is the definitive diagnostic imaging modality.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstone ileus is a rare complication of cholecystitis where a gallstone erodes through the gallbladder wall into the adjacent bowel (most commonly duodenum), creating a cholecystoenteric fistula. The stone then migrates distally, typically lodging in the terminal ileum, causing mechanical small bowel obstruction. CT is superior as it can visualize the obstructing gallstone, the cholecystoenteric fistula, and the site of obstruction, confirming the diagnosis and guiding surgical planning.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Gastrograffin studies are primarily used to confirm obstruction or evaluate for perforation, but they are not the initial diagnostic test of choice for suspected gallstone ileus when CT is available and superior for identifying the stone and fistula.\nOption B (Incorrect): Barium swallow is used to evaluate the esophagus and stomach, not the small bowel for obstruction or gallstone ileus.\nOption D (Incorrect): Abdominal ultrasound is often limited by bowel gas in cases of obstruction and is less sensitive than CT for localizing the obstructing gallstone and identifying a cholecystoenteric fistula.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Imaging Modality | Primary Use in SBO/Gallstone Ileus | Limitations |\n| :--------------- | :--------------------------------- | :---------- |\n| Plain X-ray      | Initial screen, air-fluid levels, pneumobilia | Low sensitivity for cause, stone |\n| Ultrasound       | Gallbladder pathology, limited SBO | Bowel gas, poor for distal SBO/stone |\n| CT Scan          | Definitive diagnosis, stone, fistula, obstruction site | Radiation exposure |\n| Gastrograffin Study | Confirm obstruction, rule out leak, therapeutic in some SBO | Not primary for gallstone ileus diagnosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Obstruction + pneumobilia = Gallstone ileus. CT is your diagnostic friend.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, gallstone ileus often presents with Rigler's triad: pneumobilia, small bowel obstruction, and an ectopic gallstone. The obstructing stone is typically seen in the terminal ileum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Small Bowel Obstruction (2017) recommend CT as the gold standard for diagnosis and etiology of SBO.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gastrograffin test | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Barium swallow | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Abdominal CT | ✅ Correct |\n| D | US | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Go for CT in gallstone illeus.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
