  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When AST doubles ALT in a drinker, alcohol is the culprit!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, alcoholic hepatitis. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the classic AST:ALT ratio of 2:1 or greater in a patient with a history of alcohol use, even if only on weekends, and abnormal LFTs.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAlcoholic hepatitis is characterized by hepatocellular injury due to excessive alcohol consumption. Ethanol metabolism generates reactive oxygen species and acetaldehyde, leading to hepatocyte damage and inflammation. The disproportionate elevation of AST over ALT (typically a 2:1 ratio or higher) is a hallmark feature, as alcohol depletes pyridoxal phosphate, a cofactor for ALT, more significantly than for AST. While ferritin can be elevated as an acute phase reactant in liver injury, the specific AST:ALT ratio in a drinker points directly to alcohol as the primary etiology.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (hemochromatosis) (Incorrect): While the patient has high ferritin and slightly high iron/TIBC, the classic AST:ALT ratio of 2:1 in a patient who drinks alcohol strongly points away from hemochromatosis as the primary cause of the acute LFT derangement. Hemochromatosis typically presents with very high ferritin, but the liver enzyme pattern is not specific for this condition, and the AST/ALT ratio would not typically be 2:1.\nOption C (cholangitis) (Incorrect): Cholangitis is an infection of the bile ducts, usually presenting with fever, jaundice, and right upper quadrant pain (Charcot's triad), and would typically show a cholestatic pattern of LFTs (elevated alkaline phosphatase and GGT) rather than predominantly transaminase elevation with a specific AST:ALT ratio.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Alcoholic Hepatitis | Hemochromatosis | NAFLD |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **AST:ALT Ratio** | >2:1 (often 3:1 or higher) | Variable, often <1 | <1 (often 0.8) |\n| **Ferritin** | Elevated (acute phase reactant) | Markedly elevated (>1000), high transferrin saturation | Elevated (often with insulin resistance) |\n| **Alcohol Use** | Present, often chronic/heavy | Not directly causative | Not directly causative, but can coexist |\n| **Key Diagnostic Clue** | AST:ALT ratio in drinker | High ferritin + high transferrin saturation | Metabolic syndrome, imaging (fatty liver) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: AST/ALT ratio >2:1 in a drinker? Think alcoholic hepatitis first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (ultrasound, CT, or MRI) in alcoholic hepatitis may show hepatomegaly, fatty infiltration (steatosis), and in chronic cases, signs of cirrhosis such as nodularity, ascites, and splenomegaly. There are no images provided in this question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD (American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases) 2019 Practice Guidance for the Management of Alcoholic Liver Disease recommends corticosteroids for severe alcoholic hepatitis based on Maddrey Discriminant Function or MELD score.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | hemochromatosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | alcoholic hepatitis | ✅ Correct |\n| C | cholangitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) AST/ALT ratio  2:1? Alcoholic hepatitis. If the labs simply showed high ferritin the answer would be** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
