  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When UC meets strictures, think PSC – the beaded bile duct culprit!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis (PSC). The combination of ulcerative colitis (UC) and characteristic intra- and extrahepatic duct strictures on MRCP is highly diagnostic for PSC.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrimary Sclerosing Cholangitis is a chronic cholestatic liver disease characterized by inflammation and fibrosis of the bile ducts, leading to multifocal strictures and dilations. It has a strong association with inflammatory bowel disease, particularly ulcerative colitis, which is present in 70-80% of PSC patients. MRCP is the diagnostic modality of choice for PSC, revealing the classic 'beading' pattern of strictures and dilations in both intrahepatic and extrahepatic bile ducts, which is precisely what is described in the question.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cirrhosis): Incorrect. Cirrhosis is an end-stage liver disease that can be a consequence of untreated PSC, but it is not the primary diagnosis based on the presence of bile duct strictures. The strictures themselves are indicative of PSC.\nOption B (Primary biliary cholangitis): Incorrect. Primary biliary cholangitis (PBC) primarily affects small intrahepatic bile ducts and is not associated with ulcerative colitis. MRCP would typically be normal or show only non-specific changes in PBC, not the large duct strictures seen here.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis (PSC) | Primary Biliary Cholangitis (PBC) | Autoimmune Hepatitis (AIH) |\n|---------------------|--------------------------------------|-----------------------------------|----------------------------|\n| Associated IBD      | Ulcerative Colitis (70-80%)          | No                                | No                         |\n| Bile Duct Affected  | Large intra/extrahepatic             | Small intrahepatic                | Hepatocytes                |\n| MRCP Findings       | Multifocal strictures, \"beading\"     | Normal (early), ductopenia (late) | Normal                     |\n| Autoantibodies      | p-ANCA (variable)                    | AMA (anti-mitochondrial)          | ANA, ASMA                  |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: UC + MRCP strictures = PSC until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nMRCP in PSC characteristically shows multifocal, short, annular strictures alternating with normal or slightly dilated segments, creating a 'beaded' appearance of both intrahepatic and extrahepatic bile ducts.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) Practice Guidance on Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis (2023). Recommends MRCP as the primary non-invasive diagnostic tool for PSC.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cirrhosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Primary biliary cholangitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Primary sclerosing cholangitis | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) First, we have to do an US. Afterwards, for further workup it depends: Autoimmune hepatitis -> ANA, ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
