  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Drain the unstable, operate on the stable.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis debrief accepts that US-guided cholecystostomy tube is the correct management for an unstable patient with acute cholecystitis. The patient's recent MI and CCU admission indicate significant comorbidities, making a definitive surgical procedure too risky.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute cholecystitis in a critically ill patient often requires a temporizing measure to decompress the gallbladder and control sepsis without the physiological stress of a major operation. US-guided cholecystostomy provides percutaneous drainage, reducing inflammation and infection, thereby stabilizing the patient. This allows for optimization of their medical condition before considering a definitive cholecystectomy, which may be performed later or not at all if the patient remains high risk.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Urgent open cholecystectomy) (Incorrect): This patient is in the CCU after an MI and has pneumonia, indicating severe instability and high surgical risk. An urgent open cholecystectomy would impose significant physiological stress, increasing morbidity and mortality in this critically ill individual.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Percutaneous Cholecystostomy | Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Patient Stability** | Unstable, critically ill, high surgical risk | Stable, low-moderate surgical risk |\n| **Invasiveness** | Minimally invasive, local anesthesia | Moderately invasive, general anesthesia |\n| **Goal** | Decompression, source control, temporizing | Definitive treatment, gallbladder removal |\n| **Indications** | Acute cholecystitis in high-risk patients | Symptomatic cholelithiasis, acute cholecystitis in stable patients |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unstable cholecystitis patients get drainage, not definitive surgery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, acute cholecystitis is characterized by gallbladder wall thickening (>3-4mm), pericholecystic fluid, gallstones, and a sonographic Murphy's sign. The cholecystostomy tube is placed under US guidance into the gallbladder lumen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis recommend percutaneous cholecystostomy for Grade II or III acute cholecystitis in patients with severe comorbidities or who are critically ill.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | US guided cholecystostomy tube | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Urgent open cholecystectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) This ICU patient is unable to tolerate lap chole, so go for cholecystostomy tube.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
