  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the liver's riddled, check the colon for the culprit!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nColonoscopy is the correct answer. New onset jaundice and weight loss with diffuse liver lesions (70%) in an elderly patient strongly suggest metastatic disease. Colorectal cancer is the most common primary source for liver metastases, making colonoscopy the most appropriate initial investigation to find the primary tumor.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe liver's dual blood supply (portal vein and hepatic artery) makes it a frequent site for metastases, especially from gastrointestinal cancers. Colorectal cancer cells commonly spread via the portal venous system to the liver. Identifying the primary source is crucial for accurate staging, prognosis, and guiding appropriate treatment strategies, which can range from chemotherapy to surgical resection of the primary and/or metastases. Symptoms like jaundice and weight loss often indicate advanced disease.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Upper GI endoscopy) (Incorrect): While upper GI cancers can metastasize to the liver, colorectal cancer is statistically the most common primary source for liver metastases, especially with diffuse involvement.\nOption C (Percutaneous liver biopsy) (Incorrect): A biopsy would confirm malignancy but does not identify the primary source, which is essential for comprehensive management. It is often performed after initial imaging and search for primary.\nOption D (Diagnostic laparoscopy) (Incorrect): This is an invasive procedure primarily used for staging or obtaining biopsies when less invasive methods are insufficient. It is not the most appropriate initial investigation to find the primary tumor.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Primary Cancer | Typical Presentation | Initial Investigation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Colorectal | Weight loss, jaundice, anemia, change in bowel habits | Colonoscopy |\n| Pancreatic | Jaundice, weight loss, abdominal pain, steatorrhea | CT abdomen/pelvis, EUS |\n| Breast | Palpable mass, abnormal mammogram, axillary lymphadenopathy | Mammogram, biopsy |\n| Lung | Cough, dyspnea, hemoptysis, chest pain | Chest X-ray, CT chest |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Diffuse liver mets? Think colon first, scope it.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, liver metastases typically appear as multiple, often hypodense lesions that may show peripheral enhancement or a 'target sign' after contrast administration. The 'lesions in 70% of the liver' indicates widespread involvement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colon Cancer (2023): For suspected metastatic colorectal cancer, colonoscopy is recommended for diagnosis and staging of the primary tumor, even in the presence of widespread metastatic disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Colonscopy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Upper GI endoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Percutanous liver biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Diagnostic laproscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A case of metastatic liver cancer. Colorectal cancer is the most common cancer metastasizing to the ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
