  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the liver's scarred and AFP's high, HCC's the culprit, don't ask why!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nHepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) is the correct diagnosis. The clinical scenario of an alcoholic patient with cirrhosis, right hypochondriac pain, weight loss, and elevated alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) with multiple liver lesions on CT is a classic presentation for HCC.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHCC frequently arises in the setting of chronic liver disease, particularly cirrhosis, which is often a consequence of chronic alcohol abuse. Alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) is a well-established tumor marker for HCC, and its elevation in this context is highly suggestive. The presence of multiple lesions on CT within a cirrhotic liver further solidifies the diagnosis, as HCC can be multifocal or represent intrahepatic metastases.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (pancreatic cancer) (Incorrect): Pancreatic cancer would not typically present with elevated alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) or primary multiple lesions within a cirrhotic liver. While pancreatic cancer can metastasize to the liver, the primary tumor would be in the pancreas, and AFP is not its characteristic tumor marker.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hepatocellular Carcinoma | Pancreatic Cancer |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Risk Factors** | Cirrhosis (alcohol, viral hepatitis, NAFLD) | Smoking, chronic pancreatitis, obesity, family history |\n| **Common Tumor Marker** | Alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) | CA 19-9 |\n| **Typical Imaging Findings** | Liver lesions (often with arterial hyperenhancement/venous washout), cirrhotic liver morphology | Pancreatic mass, often with biliary/pancreatic duct dilation |\n| **Primary Organ Involved** | Liver | Pancreas |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cirrhosis + elevated AFP + liver lesions = HCC until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe CT scan showing multiple lesions in the liver and cirrhosis is highly indicative. On CT, HCC lesions often demonstrate characteristic arterial phase hyperenhancement followed by venous phase washout. Cirrhosis is typically seen as a nodular liver contour, caudate lobe hypertrophy, and signs of portal hypertension.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD (American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases) Practice Guidance for the Management of Hepatocellular Carcinoma (2018). These guidelines provide diagnostic criteria for HCC based on imaging features and AFP levels in patients with cirrhosis, as well as surveillance recommendations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hepatocellular carcinoma | ✅ Correct |\n| B | pancreatic cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
