  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Resect HCC if you can, it's the best plan for cure.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Surgical resection. For a solitary hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) of this size, surgical resection offers the best chance for cure in a patient with adequate liver reserve, even in the setting of chronic Hepatitis C.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSurgical resection is the gold standard for curative treatment of solitary HCC in patients with preserved liver function. The decision for resection hinges on tumor characteristics (size, number, vascular invasion) and, critically, the patient's liver functional reserve, often assessed by Child-Pugh score, MELD score, and indocyanine green (ICG) retention test. Achieving clear oncologic margins while preserving sufficient functional liver parenchyma is paramount to prevent recurrence and post-hepatectomy liver failure. The presence of chronic Hepatitis C necessitates careful evaluation for underlying cirrhosis, which can impact resectability and increase the risk of complications.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Chemotherapy) (Incorrect): Systemic chemotherapy has historically shown limited efficacy for HCC and is generally reserved for advanced, unresectable disease or as palliative treatment, not as a primary curative option for a localized tumor.\nOption B (Radiotherapy) (Incorrect): External beam radiotherapy or SBRT can be used for HCC, particularly for unresectable tumors, those unsuitable for other local therapies, or for palliative purposes. However, it is not typically considered the 'best management' for a potentially resectable tumor when surgical resection offers a higher chance of cure.\nOption C (Transcatheter arterial chemoembolization (TACE)) (Incorrect): TACE is a common treatment for intermediate-stage HCC (BCLC stage B), often for multifocal tumors or large tumors not amenable to resection or ablation. It aims to control tumor growth, downstage, or serve as a bridge to transplantation, but it is generally not considered curative in the same way as surgical resection for a solitary tumor.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment Modality | Indication (General) | Goal |\n|---|---|---|\n| Surgical Resection | Solitary HCC, good liver function, no vascular invasion | Curative |\n| Liver Transplantation | Early HCC (Milan criteria), end-stage liver disease | Curative |\n| TACE | Intermediate HCC (multifocal, large unresectable), bridge to transplant | Disease control, downstaging, palliative |\n| Systemic Therapy (Chemo/Immunotherapy) | Advanced HCC, extrahepatic spread | Palliative, survival prolongation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For solitary HCC, surgical resection offers the best chance for cure if liver function allows.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, HCC typically shows arterial phase enhancement and venous washout. Intraoperatively, careful palpation and intraoperative ultrasound are crucial to confirm tumor location, assess vascular relationships, and ensure adequate resection margins.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) 2018 Practice Guidance for the Management of Hepatocellular Carcinoma recommends surgical resection for solitary HCC in patients with preserved liver function.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Chemotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Radiotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Transcatheter arterial chemoembolization (TACE) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Surgical resection | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
