  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cured HCV doesn't cure cirrhosis's cancer risk.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, regular screening with ultrasound. This patient has a history of liver cirrhosis, which is a significant and persistent risk factor for hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC), even after successful treatment and eradication of Hepatitis C.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCirrhosis, regardless of its etiology, is the strongest risk factor for developing HCC. Even after successful antiviral therapy for Hepatitis C, the underlying architectural distortion of the liver persists, maintaining the elevated risk of malignancy. Regular ultrasound screening, typically performed every 6 months, is the recommended surveillance strategy for cirrhotic patients. This non-invasive imaging modality is effective in detecting early-stage HCC, allowing for timely intervention and improved patient outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Regular screening with AFP alone is not sufficient for HCC surveillance due to its low sensitivity and specificity. It is often used as an adjunct to imaging but not as a standalone screening tool.\nOption C (Incorrect): Liver biopsy is an invasive diagnostic procedure, not a routine screening method for HCC. It carries risks and is not appropriate for regular follow-up.\nOption D (Incorrect): No follow-up is required (Incorrect): This is incorrect. Cirrhosis is a pre-malignant condition, and lifelong surveillance for HCC is essential, even after viral eradication, due to the persistent risk.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Patient Group | HCC Risk | Recommended Surveillance | Frequency |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Cirrhosis (any etiology) | High | Ultrasound (with or without AFP) | Every 6 months |\n| Chronic Hepatitis B (non-cirrhotic, high risk) | Moderate-High | Ultrasound (with or without AFP) | Every 6 months |\n| Chronic Hepatitis C (non-cirrhotic, cured) | Low | No routine surveillance | N/A |\n| Chronic Hepatitis C (cirrhotic, cured) | High | Ultrasound (with or without AFP) | Every 6 months |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cirrhosis means HCC surveillance, always.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, we would be looking for new focal lesions, changes in existing nodules, or features suggestive of HCC such as a hypoechoic or heterogeneous mass, often with a peripheral halo or vascular invasion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD (American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases) 2018 Practice Guidance on Hepatocellular Carcinoma. It recommends ultrasound with or without AFP every 6 months for patients with cirrhosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Regular screening with AFP | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Regular screening with ultrasound | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Liver biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | No follow up is required | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Due to the presence of cirrhosis.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
