  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Scan for cancer, don't blast for it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Abdominal US. For hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) screening in patients with cirrhosis, abdominal ultrasound is the recommended first-line diagnostic test due to its non-invasive nature and efficacy in surveillance.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAbdominal ultrasound serves as the primary screening tool for HCC in high-risk populations, such as those with cirrhosis, because it is non-invasive, readily available, and does not involve ionizing radiation or nephrotoxic contrast. Its role is to detect suspicious lesions early, allowing for timely follow-up with more definitive diagnostic imaging. Regular ultrasound surveillance has been shown to improve early detection rates and overall survival in patients with HCC.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Triphasic CT is a highly sensitive and specific imaging modality for characterizing and diagnosing HCC, especially for lesions detected on screening. However, it is not the primary screening test due to its use of ionizing radiation, higher cost, and need for intravenous contrast, making it less suitable for routine surveillance.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | HCC Screening (Ultrasound) | HCC Diagnosis/Characterization (Triphasic CT/MRI) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Purpose | Early detection of suspicious lesions in high-risk patients | Confirm diagnosis, characterize lesions, stage disease |\n| Modality | Abdominal Ultrasound | Triphasic CT, Multiphasic MRI |\n| Radiation | None | Ionizing radiation (CT) |\n| Contrast | No | IV contrast required |\n| Frequency | Every 6 months | As needed for suspicious findings |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Screening is US, diagnosis is CT/MRI.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn abdominal ultrasound for HCC screening, one would look for new or growing focal liver lesions, changes in liver contour, or signs of portal vein thrombosis. HCC typically appears as a hypoechoic or mixed echogenicity mass, often with a hypoechoic halo.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD (American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases) 2018 Practice Guidance for Hepatocellular Carcinoma recommends ultrasound with or without alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) every 6 months for HCC surveillance in high-risk patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Abdominal US | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Triphasic CT | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Screening? Ultrasound. Confirmatory? Triphasic CT. Could be a bad recall, but since it mentioned scr** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
