  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Daughter cysts mean deroofing, not just a poke!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nFor a large hydatid cyst (10x13 cm) containing daughter cysts, surgical deroofing is the most appropriate management. This approach effectively removes the parasitic elements while preserving liver parenchyma, addressing the complexity introduced by the daughter cysts.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSurgical deroofing involves careful aspiration of the cyst fluid, followed by injection of a scolicidal agent (e.g., hypertonic saline or 95% ethanol) to kill protoscolices and daughter cysts. The cyst's outer fibrous layer (pericyst) is then partially resected (deroofed), and the endocyst and daughter cysts are meticulously removed. The remaining cavity is often managed by omentoplasty or drainage. This technique minimizes the risk of recurrence and anaphylaxis by preventing spillage, while avoiding extensive liver resection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Percutaneous aspiration (PAIR) is generally reserved for smaller, unilocular cysts (WHO type CE1 or CE3a) without complicated features. For a large cyst with multiple daughter cysts (likely CE2 or CE3b), PAIR carries a higher risk of incomplete evacuation, spillage, and recurrence, making it less effective and potentially hazardous.\nOption C (Incorrect): Right hepatectomy is an aggressive procedure involving major liver resection. While curative, it is typically reserved for very complex cases such as cysts involving major vascular structures, recurrent disease, or those that have caused significant parenchymal destruction, which is not indicated in this scenario. Deroofing offers a less invasive yet effective surgical solution.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment Modality | Indication | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| PAIR (Percutaneous Aspiration, Injection, Reaspiration) | Small, unilocular cysts (CE1, CE3a) | Minimally invasive, outpatient | Risk of spillage, recurrence, not for complex cysts |\n| Surgical Deroofing (Partial Pericystectomy) | Large, symptomatic cysts, cysts with daughter cysts (CE2, CE3b) | Effective, preserves parenchyma, low recurrence | More invasive than PAIR, risk of bile leak/infection |\n| Hepatectomy (Resection) | Complicated cysts, recurrent disease, major vascular involvement, destroyed parenchyma | Curative, removes entire cyst/pericyst | Highly invasive, significant morbidity/mortality |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Large hydatid cysts with daughter cysts demand surgical deroofing, not just aspiration.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, a hydatid cyst with daughter cysts (WHO type CE2 or CE3b) appears as a multivesicular or septated lesion, often described as a \"wheel-spoke\" or \"honeycomb\" appearance. Intraoperatively, after deroofing the pericyst, the endocyst containing numerous smaller, spherical daughter cysts floating in clear hydatid fluid would be visible.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe World Health Organization (WHO) Informal Working Group on Echinococcosis (IWGE) guidelines (e.g., 2001, updated in various forms) recommend surgical intervention, particularly deroofing, for large, symptomatic cysts with daughter cysts (CE2, CE3b) that are not amenable to PAIR.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Surgical deroofing | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Percutaneous aspiration | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Right hepatectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
