  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bloody stool and tenesmus? Think amoeba, not just a bug.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Amebiasis. The constellation of fever, bloody stool, tenesmus, and abdominal distention in a 7-year-old child strongly points towards an invasive colonic infection, which is characteristic of amebic dysentery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAmebiasis, caused by *Entamoeba histolytica*, is an intestinal infection that can lead to invasive colitis. The trophozoites invade the colonic mucosa, causing flask-shaped ulcers, inflammation, and necrosis. This mucosal damage results in the classic symptoms of dysentery: bloody and mucoid stools, abdominal pain, and tenesmus due to rectal inflammation. Fever indicates systemic involvement, and severe colitis can lead to abdominal distention, potentially from toxic megacolon or ileus.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Ascaris typically causes symptoms related to intestinal obstruction or migration (e.g., pulmonary symptoms), not primarily bloody stool and tenesmus.\nOption C (Incorrect): Giardiasis causes watery, greasy diarrhea and malabsorption, but rarely bloody stools or tenesmus.\nOption D (Incorrect): Rotavirus causes acute watery diarrhea and vomiting, but not bloody stools or tenesmus.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Pathogen | Key Symptoms | Stool Characteristics | Complications |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| *Entamoeba histolytica* (Amebiasis) | Fever, abdominal pain, tenesmus | Bloody, mucoid | Amebic liver abscess, toxic megacolon, intestinal perforation |\n| *Ascaris lumbricoides* (Ascariasis) | Abdominal pain, malnutrition, cough | Worms in stool/vomit | Intestinal obstruction, biliary obstruction, appendicitis |\n| *Giardia lamblia* (Giardiasis) | Chronic diarrhea, bloating, cramps | Watery, greasy, foul-smelling | Malabsorption, weight loss |\n| Rotavirus | Fever, vomiting, acute diarrhea | Watery | Dehydration |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bloody stool + tenesmus in a child = think invasive colitis, especially amebiasis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn colonoscopy, amebic colitis can show discrete, flask-shaped ulcers with normal intervening mucosa, or diffuse inflammation in severe cases. Abdominal X-ray might show colonic dilation in toxic megacolon.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWHO Guidelines for the treatment of amoebiasis (2003): Recommends metronidazole for invasive amebiasis, followed by a luminal amebicide.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ascaris | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Amebiasis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Giardiasis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Rotavirus | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
