  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Time heals many pseudocysts; don't rush to drain.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nObservation is the correct initial management for this patient. The pseudocyst is relatively small (4 cm) and has developed within 3 weeks of acute pancreatitis, making spontaneous resolution highly likely.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPancreatic pseudocysts are encapsulated collections of pancreatic fluid, necrotic debris, and inflammatory exudates that typically form after acute pancreatitis. For pseudocysts that are less than 6 cm in size and present for less than 6 weeks, the rate of spontaneous resolution is high, often exceeding 50%. Therefore, an initial period of watchful waiting with serial imaging is the most appropriate and least invasive approach, avoiding unnecessary interventions and their associated risks.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Internal drainage) (Incorrect): Internal drainage, such as endoscopic or surgical cystogastrostomy, is typically reserved for mature pseudocysts (usually >6 weeks old) that are symptomatic, enlarging, complicated, or fail to resolve spontaneously. It is premature at 3 weeks.\nOption C (External drainage) (Incorrect): External drainage (percutaneous or surgical) is generally indicated for infected pseudocysts or those not amenable to internal drainage, and carries risks like fistula formation. It is not indicated for an uncomplicated, small, early pseudocyst.\nOption D (Surgical remove) (Incorrect): Surgical resection of a pseudocyst is rarely performed and is reserved for highly complex cases, suspicion of malignancy, or when other drainage techniques have failed. It is an overly aggressive approach for this presentation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | < 6 weeks & < 6 cm | > 6 weeks OR > 6 cm OR Symptomatic | Infected Pseudocyst |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Management** | Observation | Internal Drainage (Endoscopic/Surgical) | External Drainage (Percutaneous/Surgical) |\n| **Rationale** | High chance of spontaneous resolution | Persistent/symptomatic, mature wall for anastomosis | Sepsis control, often bridge to definitive |\n| **Complications** | None if resolves | Bleeding, perforation, recurrence, stent migration | Fistula, superinfection, inadequate drainage |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Observe small, early pseudocysts; drain if symptomatic or persistent.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a pancreatic pseudocyst typically appears as a well-defined, anechoic or hypoechoic fluid collection with a distinct wall, usually adjacent to the pancreas. CT imaging would show a well-encapsulated fluid collection without solid components.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Pancreatitis 2013\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Observation | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Internal drainage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | External drainage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Surgical remove | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) 3 weeks and 4cm, so keep observing for now. Afterwards, go for internal drainage.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
