  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the swallow fails, a gastric tube prevails!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nGastrostomy is the correct choice for providing long-term nutritional support in patients with severe dysphagia, especially when accompanied by an absent gag reflex and evidence of chronic malnutrition (weight loss). This method ensures a safe and effective route for feeding while significantly minimizing the risk of aspiration.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA gastrostomy, commonly placed percutaneously (PEG), offers a durable and well-tolerated solution for enteral nutrition. By bypassing the oral and pharyngeal phases of swallowing, it directly addresses the high aspiration risk associated with an absent gag reflex. The stomach's natural capacity and digestive functions are utilized, allowing for flexible feeding regimens, and it is generally preferred over jejunal access unless specific gastric contraindications exist. This approach provides a stable and comfortable long-term feeding solution, improving patient quality of life and nutritional status.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Jejunostomy) (Incorrect): While providing enteral nutrition, jejunostomy is typically reserved for patients who cannot tolerate gastric feeding due to conditions such as severe gastroparesis, gastric outlet obstruction, or a high risk of aspiration even with gastric tube feeds. It is a more complex procedure and not the first-line choice when gastric function is presumed intact.\nOption C (NGT) (Incorrect): Nasogastric tubes are suitable for short-term nutritional support (typically less than 4-6 weeks). For a patient with an absent gag reflex and chronic weight loss, indicating a need for long-term feeding, an NGT carries a high risk of aspiration, discomfort, and is prone to dislodgement, making it an inappropriate long-term solution.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | NGT (Nasogastric Tube) | Gastrostomy (e.g., PEG) | Jejunostomy |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Duration** | Short-term (<4-6 weeks) | Long-term (>4-6 weeks) | Long-term (>4-6 weeks) |\n| **Aspiration Risk** | High, especially with absent gag reflex | Low, bypasses upper airway | Low, bypasses upper airway and stomach |\n| **Indications** | Temporary feeding, gastric decompression | Dysphagia, intact gastric function, long-term need | Gastric intolerance, severe gastroparesis, high aspiration risk with gastric feeds |\n| **Procedure** | Bedside, non-surgical | Endoscopic or surgical | Surgical |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Absent gag reflex + chronic weight loss = long-term gastrostomy for safe nutrition.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring percutaneous endoscopic gastrostomy (PEG) placement, endoscopy visualizes the stomach wall for transillumination and direct puncture, confirming proper tube position. Fluoroscopy can also be used for surgical gastrostomy placement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASPEN Guidelines for the Provision and Assessment of Nutrition Support Therapy in the Adult Critically Ill Patient (2016) recommend early enteral nutrition and guide appropriate access routes based on anticipated duration and patient condition.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gastrostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Jejunostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | NGT | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
