  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Two years of stability means benignity; put the CT scanner away!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C is correct. A lung nodule that has remained stable in size for at least two years, especially if small and in an asymptomatic patient, is overwhelmingly likely to be benign and requires no further follow-up.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Fleischner Society Guidelines provide evidence-based recommendations for the management of incidentally detected lung nodules. A key principle is that a solid lung nodule, regardless of size, that demonstrates stability (no change in size) over a two-year period has an extremely low probability of malignancy, typically less than 1%. This stability period is considered sufficient to confidently classify the nodule as benign, thus obviating the need for further surveillance, reducing patient anxiety, radiation exposure, and healthcare costs.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Pet scan) (Incorrect): A PET scan is generally not indicated for small, stable, incidentally discovered lung nodules due to low metabolic activity and high false-positive rates, especially in benign lesions. It would expose the patient to unnecessary radiation and cost.\nOption B (Follow up) (Incorrect): Continued follow-up is unnecessary for a nodule that has demonstrated stability for two years. The risk of malignancy is negligible, and further surveillance offers no clinical benefit.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nodule Characteristic | Recommendation (Fleischner) | Rationale |\n| :-------------------- | :-------------------------- | :-------- |\n| Solid, <6mm, low risk | No routine follow-up | Very low malignancy risk |\n| Solid, 6-8mm, low risk | CT at 6-12 months, then 18-24 months if stable | Assess stability over time |\n| Solid, >8mm, low risk | CT at 3 months, then 9 months, then annually for 2 years if stable | Higher baseline risk, requires closer initial surveillance |\n| Solid, any size, stable for 2 years | No further follow-up | Malignancy highly unlikely |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stable for 2 years? No more fears!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT imaging, a stable 8mm lung nodule would appear as a well-defined, solid lesion with no change in diameter or morphology over serial scans spanning at least two years. Absence of growth is the key imaging feature.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nFleischner Society Guidelines 2017: For solid nodules, stability for 2 years indicates benignity and no further follow-up is needed.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pet scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Follow up | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | No need to follow Up | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) No change in the size for 2 years.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
