  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't poke a small, quiet nodule; watch it grow, or not.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is repeat CT scan within 3-6 months. This approach aligns with current guidelines for managing small, solid lung nodules in low-risk individuals, prioritizing surveillance over immediate invasive procedures.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe management of incidentally detected lung nodules is primarily guided by the Fleischner Society guidelines, which stratify recommendations based on nodule size, morphology (solid, subsolid), and patient risk factors (smoking history, age, emphysema, family history of lung cancer). For a 7mm solid nodule in a 32-year-old non-smoker, the risk of malignancy is low, making surveillance with serial CT scans the appropriate initial strategy to monitor for growth or changes suggestive of malignancy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Pulmonary function tests are used to assess lung function and are not indicated for the initial evaluation or management of an isolated lung nodule.\nOption C (Incorrect): Biopsy of the lesion is an invasive procedure and is generally reserved for larger, suspicious nodules or those that show growth on follow-up, especially in higher-risk patients. It is too aggressive for a 7mm nodule in a low-risk patient.\nOption D (Incorrect): PET scans have limited sensitivity for small nodules (<8-10mm) and can yield false negatives, particularly in low-risk patients. Therefore, it is not recommended as the initial diagnostic step for a 7mm nodule.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nodule Size (Solid) | Low-Risk Patient (Non-smoker) | High-Risk Patient (Smoker, etc.) |\n| :------------------ | :---------------------------- | :------------------------------- |\n| < 6 mm              | No routine follow-up          | Follow-up CT at 12 months        |\n| 6-8 mm              | Follow-up CT at 6-12 months   | Follow-up CT at 6-12 months, then 18-24 months |\n| > 8 mm              | Follow-up CT at 3 months, then 9 months, or PET/biopsy | PET/biopsy/surgical resection |\n| Subsolid Nodule     | Different guidelines apply, often longer follow-up | Different guidelines apply, often longer follow-up |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Small, solid nodules in low-risk patients get serial CTs, not immediate invasion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a lung nodule appears as a rounded or irregular opacity within the lung parenchyma. Follow-up CT scans are crucial to assess for changes in size, shape, or density, which can indicate malignancy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nFleischner Society Guidelines 2017. These guidelines provide evidence-based recommendations for the management of incidental pulmonary nodules detected on CT scans.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Repeat CT scan within 3-6 months | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Pulmonary funtion test | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Biopsy of the lesion | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | PET scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) 0.5mm - 0.7mm = CT\nIf 0.4mm or below? No need for follow up.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
