  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt post-RYGB, CT it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient's presentation with fever, chills, and left shoulder pain 3 days post-Roux-en-Y surgery is highly suggestive of an anastomotic leak or intra-abdominal abscess. A CT scan with oral and IV contrast is the best initial diagnostic investigation to identify and localize these critical complications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCT with contrast provides superior anatomical detail, allowing for the detection of contrast extravasation from the gastrojejunal or jejunojejunal anastomoses, which is the hallmark of a leak. It can also precisely identify and characterize perianastomotic fluid collections, abscesses, or other inflammatory changes within the abdominal cavity. This detailed visualization is crucial for guiding subsequent therapeutic interventions, even in the presence of mild hypotension, as the urgency of diagnosis for a potential septic source outweighs the risk of contrast nephropathy in this acute setting.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Endoscopy) (Incorrect): While useful for evaluating mucosal integrity and intraluminal leaks, endoscopy is less effective for detecting extraluminal collections or leaks into the peritoneal cavity, especially in the early postoperative period. It is more indicated for suspected leaks after sleeve gastrectomy or for later complications like strictures.\nOption C (Laparoscopy) (Incorrect): Laparoscopy is a surgical intervention, not primarily a diagnostic investigation in this acute setting. It is invasive and typically reserved for therapeutic intervention after a diagnosis is made or when imaging is inconclusive.\nOption D (Exploratory laparotomy) (Incorrect): This is the most invasive surgical approach and should be reserved as a last resort for cases of hemodynamic instability with clear signs of peritonitis, or when other diagnostic and less invasive therapeutic options have failed. It is not the best initial diagnostic investigation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Primary Use in Post-RYGB Complications | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| CT with Contrast | Suspected leak, abscess, intra-abdominal collection | Excellent anatomical detail, detects extraluminal pathology, guides intervention | Radiation exposure, contrast nephropathy risk, less sensitive for very small leaks |\n| Endoscopy | Suspected intraluminal leak (e.g., sleeve), stricture, bleeding | Direct visualization of mucosa, therapeutic potential (stenting) | Invasive, limited view of extraluminal space, risk of perforation |\n| Laparoscopy | Diagnostic when imaging inconclusive, therapeutic intervention | Direct visualization of peritoneal cavity, allows for repair/drainage | Invasive, general anesthesia required, risk of injury |\n| Upper GI Series (Gastrografin) | Suspected leak, especially early post-op | Can confirm leak, less invasive than endoscopy | Less anatomical detail than CT, aspiration risk, not good for collections |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Fever, chills, shoulder pain post-RYGB = leak until proven otherwise; CT with contrast is your first step.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT with contrast, one would look for extravasation of oral or IV contrast material from the gastrojejunal anastomosis or staple lines, perianastomotic fluid collections, abscesses (often with gas bubbles), or signs of generalized peritonitis. Free fluid or air not explained by surgery would also be concerning.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASMBS Position Statement on the Prevention, Detection, and Management of Gastrointestinal Leaks After Bariatric Surgery (2016): Recommends prompt investigation with imaging (e.g., CT with oral and IV contrast) for suspected leaks.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT with contrast | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Endoscy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Laparoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Exploratory laparatomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A, even if the blood pressure is 90/60 in another recall. If the patient presented after \nsleeve, go** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
