  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Sleeve surgery, sticky situation: think adhesions!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct diagnosis is adhesions, as this patient presents with classic symptoms of small bowel obstruction (SBO) following a laparoscopic sleeve gastrectomy. Any prior abdominal surgery, even laparoscopic, is a significant risk factor for adhesion formation, which is the most common cause of SBO in patients with a surgical history.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdhesions are fibrous bands that form between abdominal organs or between organs and the abdominal wall as a result of peritoneal injury and inflammation during surgery. These bands can entrap, kink, or compress loops of small bowel, leading to mechanical obstruction. The patient's symptoms of central abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, distension, and exaggerated bowel sounds are all consistent with SBO, and the surgical history points directly to adhesions as the etiology.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incisional hernia) (Incorrect): While a previous surgery is a risk factor, laparoscopic sleeve gastrectomy typically involves small incisions, making a significant incisional hernia causing SBO less likely than adhesions. The pain is central, not necessarily localized to an incision.\nOption B (Internal hernia) (Incorrect): Internal hernias are a well-known complication of Roux-en-Y gastric bypass due to created mesenteric defects (e.g., Petersen's defect, transverse mesocolon defect), but they are exceedingly rare after a sleeve gastrectomy where the bowel anatomy is not rearranged in the same manner.\nOption C (Intussusception) (Incorrect): Intussusception is rare in adults and typically requires a lead point (e.g., tumor, Meckel's diverticulum). While possible, it is a far less common cause of SBO in a patient with prior abdominal surgery compared to adhesions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of SBO | Associated Bariatric Surgery | Mechanism | Key Feature |\n|:---------------|:-----------------------------|:----------|:------------|\n| Adhesions      | Sleeve Gastrectomy, Laparotomy | Peritoneal trauma/inflammation | Most common SBO cause post-abdominal surgery |\n| Internal Hernia| Roux-en-Y Gastric Bypass     | Mesenteric defects (Petersen's, transverse mesocolon) | High mortality if delayed diagnosis |\n| Intussusception| Rare in adults               | Lead point (tumor, Meckel's) | \"Target sign\" on CT, rare post-bariatric |\n| Incisional Hernia| Any abdominal surgery        | Fascial defect at incision site | Palpable mass, localized pain, less common with laparoscopic |\n\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sleeve gastrectomy SBO = adhesions. Roux-en-Y SBO = internal hernia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCT scan findings for SBO include dilated small bowel loops (>3 cm), air-fluid levels, and a transition point with collapsed distal bowel. Intraoperatively, one would identify fibrous bands (adhesions) kinking or compressing the small bowel, leading to obstruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) guidelines for the management of small bowel obstruction (2017) recommend early diagnosis and management, often involving surgical intervention for complete or complicated SBO.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Incisional hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Internal hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Intussusception | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Adhesion | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Hx of sleeve. If hx of roux-en Y, choose internal hernia.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
