  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, check the flow out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Ankle-Brachial Index (ABI). For an elderly male with hypertension presenting with a lateral malleolus ulcer, the primary concern is often peripheral arterial disease (PAD), and ABI is the recommended initial screening test.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Ankle-Brachial Index (ABI) is a simple, non-invasive, and cost-effective physiological test that compares the blood pressure in the ankles to the blood pressure in the arms. A low ABI (typically <0.9) indicates reduced blood flow to the lower extremities, strongly suggesting PAD as the underlying cause of the ulcer. It serves as an excellent screening tool to identify the presence and severity of arterial insufficiency before proceeding to more advanced imaging.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (CT-A) (Incorrect): CT angiography is an invasive test involving radiation and contrast, typically reserved for surgical planning after PAD has been confirmed and localized by non-invasive means like ABI and duplex ultrasound.\nOption C (US duplex) (Incorrect): While duplex ultrasound is excellent for localizing and characterizing arterial stenoses, it is usually performed after an abnormal ABI confirms the presence of PAD. ABI is a more appropriate initial screening test.\nOption D (VT venogram) (Incorrect): A venogram is used to visualize the venous system and diagnose venous thrombosis or insufficiency. A lateral malleolus ulcer in an elderly patient with hypertension is highly suggestive of arterial disease, not venous, making a venogram irrelevant as a first test.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Test | Purpose | Invasiveness | Role in PAD Diagnosis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| ABI | Initial screening for PAD | Non-invasive | First-line test to detect presence and severity |\n| US Duplex | Localize and characterize stenoses | Non-invasive | Follows ABI for detailed anatomical assessment |\n| CT-A | Detailed anatomical mapping | Invasive (radiation, contrast) | Pre-operative planning for revascularization |\n| VT Venogram | Diagnose venous disease | Invasive (contrast) | Not indicated for arterial ulcers |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always start with ABI for suspected PAD before advanced imaging.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nAn ABI involves measuring systolic blood pressure at the brachial artery and at the dorsalis pedis and posterior tibial arteries. The ratio of ankle to brachial pressure is calculated. A normal ABI is 1.0-1.4, while an ABI <0.9 is diagnostic of PAD. An ABI >1.4 may indicate calcified, non-compressible arteries, requiring further evaluation like toe-brachial index.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2016 AHA/ACC Guideline on the Management of Patients With Lower Extremity Peripheral Artery Disease recommends ABI as the initial diagnostic test for PAD.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT-A | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | ABI | ✅ Correct |\n| C | US duplex | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | VT venogram | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Start with an ABI in PAD then go for an US.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
