  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Medial leg ulcers scream venous insufficiency.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Venous hypertension. This diagnosis is most likely because venous ulcers characteristically present on the medial aspect of the lower leg, often in the gaiter area, due to chronic venous insufficiency.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic venous hypertension leads to sustained elevation of pressure in the superficial and deep venous systems of the lower extremities. This pressure causes capillary leakage, fibrin cuff formation, leukocyte trapping, and ultimately tissue hypoxia and inflammation, resulting in skin changes and ulceration. The medial leg is particularly susceptible due to the anatomy of perforating veins and the hydrostatic pressure effects.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Diabetic ulcers typically occur on pressure points of the foot (e.g., plantar surface, toes, heel) due to neuropathy and ischemia, not primarily on the medial leg.\nOption C (Incorrect): Atherosclerotic (arterial) ulcers are usually painful, punched-out, and found on the toes, feet, or bony prominences, often on the lateral malleolus or dorsum of the foot, not typically the medial leg.\nOption D (Incorrect): Buerger's disease (thromboangiitis obliterans) causes ischemic ulcers primarily on the digits of the hands and feet in young smokers, not typically on the medial leg.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Venous Ulcer | Arterial Ulcer | Diabetic Ulcer |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Location** | Medial malleolus/gaiter area | Toes, feet, lateral malleolus | Plantar foot, toes, heel |\n| **Pain** | Mild to moderate, relieved by elevation | Severe, worse with elevation | Often painless (neuropathy) |\n| **Appearance** | Irregular, shallow, exudative, slough | Punched-out, well-demarcated, pale base | Calloused edges, deep, infected |\n| **Associated Signs** | Edema, hyperpigmentation, lipodermatosclerosis | Pallor, absent pulses, hair loss, cool skin | Neuropathy, foot deformities, infection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Medial leg ulcer = think venous.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuplex ultrasound is the gold standard for diagnosing venous insufficiency, showing reflux in superficial and/or deep veins, and identifying incompetent perforators. In the OR, surgical treatment for venous ulcers might involve debridement, skin grafting, or addressing underlying venous reflux (e.g., saphenous vein ablation).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) and American Venous Forum (AVF) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Venous Ulcers (2014/2022 update). These guidelines recommend compression therapy as the cornerstone of treatment and address surgical interventions for underlying reflux.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Diabetic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Venous hypertension | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Atherosclerosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Buerger's disease. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
