  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Venous ulcers: dark, viable, normal pulse, duplex first!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Venous duplex US. The clinical presentation of a non-healing ulcer with dark discoloration, a viable ulcer bed, and normal pulses strongly suggests chronic venous insufficiency, for which duplex ultrasound is the primary diagnostic tool.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic venous insufficiency leads to venous hypertension, causing extravasation of red blood cells and hemosiderin deposition (dark discoloration), lipodermatosclerosis, and ultimately ulceration, typically around the malleoli. A viable ulcer bed with normal pulses rules out critical limb ischemia as the primary cause. Venous duplex ultrasound directly visualizes venous anatomy, assesses valve function, and detects reflux or obstruction, confirming the diagnosis and guiding subsequent treatment strategies.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (CT angiogram) (Incorrect): This is an invasive test primarily used to evaluate arterial anatomy and pathology, not the initial diagnostic for suspected venous insufficiency.\nOption C (Arterial doppler US) (Incorrect): While arterial assessment is important, the clinical signs (dark discoloration, viable bed, normal pulses) point away from primary arterial disease. Venous pathology is more likely given the description.\nOption D (Conventional angiograph) (Incorrect): This is an invasive arterial study with risks, reserved for complex arterial disease or pre-intervention planning, not for initial workup of suspected venous ulcers.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Venous Ulcer | Arterial Ulcer | Neuropathic Ulcer |\n| :-------------- | :------------------------------------------ | :---------------------------------------------- | :---------------------------------------------- |\n| **Location** | Medial malleolus, gaiter area | Distal (toes, foot, lateral malleolus) | Plantar foot, metatarsal heads |\n| **Appearance** | Irregular, shallow, viable bed, exudative | Punched out, pale/necrotic base, minimal exudate | Calloused rim, deep, often infected |\n| **Skin changes**| Hyperpigmentation, lipodermatosclerosis, edema | Atrophy, hair loss, pallor on elevation, rubor | Dry, cracked skin, callus |\n| **Pulses** | Normal | Diminished or absent | Normal |\n| **Pain** | Mild to moderate, relieved by elevation | Severe, worse with elevation, relieved by dependency | Often painless (neuropathy) |\n| **Diagnosis** | Venous duplex US | ABI, Arterial duplex US, CTA/MRA | Clinical exam, nerve conduction studies |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Dark discoloration + viable ulcer + normal pulse = think venous.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nVenous duplex US would show incompetent venous valves, reflux in superficial or deep veins, and potentially venous obstruction, confirming venous hypertension.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) and American Venous Forum (AVF) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Venous Leg Ulcers (2014) recommend duplex ultrasound as the primary diagnostic tool for venous insufficiency.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT angiogram | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Venous duplex US | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Arterial doppler US | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Conventional angiograph | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) US initially. In this case, venous US because of the dark discoloration and a viable ulcer bed.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
