  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fractured hip, high DVT risk, LMWH is your best bet.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Enoxaparin 40 mg SC daily. This is the standard prophylactic dose of a low molecular weight heparin (LMWH) for preventing deep vein thrombosis (DVT) in high-risk orthopedic trauma patients, such as those with hip fractures.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHip fracture patients are at extremely high risk for DVT and subsequent pulmonary embolism due to immobility, surgical trauma, and systemic inflammatory response. Low molecular weight heparins like enoxaparin exert their anticoagulant effect primarily by inhibiting Factor Xa, leading to a more predictable anticoagulant response compared to unfractionated heparin. Its subcutaneous administration, once-daily dosing, and reduced need for monitoring make it the preferred agent for DVT prophylaxis in this setting, significantly reducing morbidity and mortality.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Aspirin 81 mg PO daily is primarily an antiplatelet agent and, while it has some role in DVT prophylaxis in specific orthopedic settings (e.g., after total joint arthroplasty), it is generally considered less effective than LMWH for high-risk trauma like hip fractures. The dose is also typically for antiplatelet effects.\nOption C (Incorrect): Fondaparinux is an effective Factor Xa inhibitor for DVT prophylaxis, but 10 mg SC daily is a therapeutic (treatment) dose, not a prophylactic dose. The standard prophylactic dose for fondaparinux is 2.5 mg SC daily.\nOption D (Incorrect): Heparin sulfate 10,000 units IV BID is a therapeutic (treatment) dose of unfractionated heparin, and IV administration is not typical for DVT prophylaxis. Prophylactic doses of unfractionated heparin are typically 5,000 units SC two or three times daily. LMWH is generally preferred over UFH for prophylaxis due to its superior pharmacokinetic profile and lower risk of heparin-induced thrombocytopenia (HIT).\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Anticoagulant | Mechanism | Typical Prophylactic Dose | Key Indication/Consideration |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Enoxaparin (LMWH) | Factor Xa inhibition | 40 mg SC daily (or 30 mg SC BID) | High-risk orthopedic trauma (e.g., hip fracture), general surgery |\n| Fondaparinux | Selective Factor Xa inhibition | 2.5 mg SC daily | High-risk orthopedic surgery, alternative to LMWH |\n| Unfractionated Heparin (UFH) | Potentiates antithrombin | 5,000 units SC BID/TID | General medical/surgical prophylaxis, renal impairment |\n| Aspirin | Irreversible COX inhibition (antiplatelet) | 81-325 mg PO daily | Post-total joint arthroplasty (alternative), lower risk prophylaxis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For hip fracture DVT prophylaxis, LMWH at prophylactic dose is the gold standard.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe question mentions \"left hip fracture (see lab results)\" but no image was provided. On plain film X-ray, a hip fracture would typically appear as a discontinuity or displacement of the femoral neck or intertrochanteric region.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline (2019) on Preventing Venous Thromboembolic Disease in Patients Undergoing Elective Hip and Knee Arthroplasty recommends LMWH or fondaparinux for DVT prophylaxis. The American College of Chest Physicians (ACCP) Guidelines (2016) also recommend LMWH for DVT prophylaxis in major orthopedic surgery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Aspirin 81 mg PO daily | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Enoxaparin 40 mg SC daily | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Fondaparinux 10 mg SC daily | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Heparin sulfate 10,000 units IV BID | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) To prevent DVT, choose a prophylactic dose as outlined earlier.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
