  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 DVT demands therapeutic action, not just prevention!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient presents with an established Deep Vein Thrombosis (DVT), necessitating immediate therapeutic anticoagulation to prevent clot propagation and pulmonary embolism. Option D, Heparin 10,000 U IV, represents a therapeutic dose, typically an initial bolus, for acute DVT treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute DVT requires therapeutic anticoagulation to inhibit further thrombus formation and reduce the risk of life-threatening pulmonary embolism. Unfractionated heparin (UFH) administered intravenously is a rapid-acting anticoagulant that potentiates antithrombin, effectively inhibiting thrombin and Factor Xa. An initial bolus, such as 10,000 units, quickly achieves therapeutic levels, followed by a continuous infusion titrated to achieve a target aPTT, making it a cornerstone of initial DVT management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Aspirin is an antiplatelet agent, not an anticoagulant, and is not used as primary treatment for acute DVT.\nOption B (Incorrect): Enoxaparin 40 mg SC is a common prophylactic dose for VTE prevention. For established DVT, the therapeutic dose is typically 1 mg/kg SC every 12 hours or 1.5 mg/kg SC once daily.\nOption C (Incorrect): While fondaparinux is used for DVT treatment, the standard therapeutic dose is 7.5 mg SC once daily for most patients (5 mg for <50 kg, 10 mg for >100 kg). 20 mg is not a standard therapeutic dose.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Anticoagulant | Prophylactic Dose (VTE) | Therapeutic Dose (DVT/PE) | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Unfractionated Heparin (UFH) | 5,000 U SC q8-12h | Initial bolus (e.g., 80 U/kg IV) then infusion (e.g., 18 U/kg/hr) | Potentiates antithrombin |\n| Enoxaparin (LMWH) | 30 mg SC q12h or 40 mg SC q24h | 1 mg/kg SC q12h or 1.5 mg/kg SC q24h | Potentiates antithrombin, primarily inhibits Factor Xa |\n| Fondaparinux | 2.5 mg SC q24h | 5 mg SC q24h (<50kg), 7.5 mg SC q24h (50-100kg), 10 mg SC q24h (>100kg) | Selective Factor Xa inhibitor |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: DVT means therapeutic dose, not prophylactic.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuplex ultrasound for DVT typically shows non-compressibility of the vein, intraluminal echogenic material (thrombus), and absent or altered flow with augmentation maneuvers.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Hematology (ASH) 2020 Guidelines for Management of Venous Thromboembolism: recommends initial parenteral anticoagulation for acute DVT.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Aspirin 61 mg | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Enoxaparin 40 mg SC | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Fondaparinux 20 mg | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hepatin 10,000 U IV | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Since the patient already has DVT, we need a therapeutic dose.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
