  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Foley for extraperitoneal, fix intraperitoneal.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct management for an uncomplicated extraperitoneal bladder injury associated with a pelvic fracture is non-operative, primarily involving catheter drainage. This approach allows the bladder to heal spontaneously by diverting urine and reducing pressure.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nExtraperitoneal bladder injuries, often caused by bony spicules from pelvic fractures, typically involve the anterior or lateral bladder wall. The rich vascular supply of the bladder, combined with the containment of urine extravasation within the extraperitoneal space, facilitates healing with simple urinary diversion. A Foley catheter decompresses the bladder, preventing further extravasation and allowing the bladder wall to coapt and repair itself over time. This conservative management avoids the risks of surgical intervention while achieving excellent outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Suprapubic catheterization is generally reserved for complex urethral injuries or when a transurethral catheter cannot be placed. For an extraperitoneal bladder injury, a transurethral Foley catheter is usually sufficient and less invasive.\nOption C (Incorrect): Surgical repair is typically indicated for intraperitoneal bladder injuries, bladder neck injuries, large extraperitoneal tears, or persistent extravasation despite catheter drainage. Simple extraperitoneal injuries heal reliably with catheter drainage alone, making immediate repair unnecessary and potentially increasing morbidity.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Extraperitoneal Bladder Injury | Intraperitoneal Bladder Injury |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Mechanism** | Pelvic fracture (bony spicules) | Direct blow to distended bladder |\n| **Location** | Anterior/lateral bladder wall, bladder neck | Bladder dome |\n| **Diagnosis** | Cystogram (extravasation confined to extraperitoneal space) | Cystogram (intraperitoneal extravasation, \"Christmas tree\" appearance) |\n| **Management** | Foley catheter drainage (2-3 weeks) | Surgical repair (laparotomy/laparoscopy) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Extraperitoneal bladder injury + pelvic fracture = Foley drainage.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA cystogram would show contrast extravasation confined to the perivesical space, outlining the bladder and not extending into the peritoneal cavity. This is crucial for differentiating it from an intraperitoneal injury.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on Urotrauma (2020) recommend non-operative management with catheter drainage for uncomplicated extraperitoneal bladder injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Suprapubic catheterization | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Catheter Drainage for 2 weeks then reassess | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Catheter drainage for 2 weeks then repair | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
