  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the urethra's torn, a Foley's scorned; suprapubic's born.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Suprapubic catheter. In a patient with a pelvic fracture and blood at the external meatus, a urethral injury is highly suspected. The most appropriate immediate action is to secure bladder drainage without manipulating the potentially injured urethra.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPosterior urethral injuries, particularly to the membranous urethra, are strongly associated with pelvic fractures due to the urethra's fixation to the puboprostatic ligaments in males. Blood at the external meatus is a classic sign of urethral trauma. Attempting to pass a Foley catheter in this scenario is absolutely contraindicated as it can convert a partial urethral tear into a complete one, create a false passage, or worsen existing injury. A suprapubic catheter provides safe and effective bladder decompression, bypassing the injured urethra and preventing further damage while definitive diagnosis and repair are planned.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cystoscopy) (Incorrect): While useful for direct visualization of the urethra, it is not the initial most appropriate action in an acute trauma setting with suspected urethral disruption. It is typically performed later for definitive evaluation or repair.\nOption B (Foley’s Catheter) (Incorrect): This is contraindicated. Attempting to pass a Foley catheter when urethral injury is suspected (indicated by blood at the meatus and pelvic fracture) can cause further damage, converting a partial tear to a complete one or creating a false passage.\nOption D (CT pelvis) (Incorrect): A CT pelvis is essential for evaluating the pelvic fracture itself, but it does not directly assess the urethral injury. The definitive diagnostic test for urethral injury is a Retrograde Urethrogram (RUG). While a CT may be part of the trauma workup, it's not the most appropriate *action* for managing the urethral injury itself, especially concerning bladder drainage.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Scenario | Initial Diagnostic Step | Initial Management (if Foley contraindicated) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Suspected Urethral Injury (blood at meatus, pelvic fracture) | Retrograde Urethrogram (RUG) | Suprapubic Catheter |\n| Confirmed Partial Urethral Injury | RUG | Gentle Foley attempt (if successful, leave in place) |\n| Confirmed Complete Urethral Injury | RUG | Suprapubic Catheter |\n| No Urethral Injury | N/A | Foley Catheter |\n| Unstable patient with suspected urethral injury | Stabilize patient, then RUG or immediate suprapubic catheter | Suprapubic Catheter |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Blood at meatus + pelvic fracture = No Foley, think suprapubic.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA Retrograde Urethrogram (RUG) would show extravasation of contrast material from the urethra, indicating the location and extent of the injury (partial vs. complete tear). A CT pelvis would demonstrate the bony pelvic fracture, which is often a predictor of posterior urethral injury.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on Urethral Trauma (2020). These guidelines recommend performing a retrograde urethrogram (RUG) in patients with suspected urethral injury and placing a suprapubic catheter for bladder drainage if a urethral catheter cannot be safely passed.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cystoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Folly’s Catheter | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Suprapubic catheter | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | CT pelvis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
