  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Urethral trauma: RUG before you tug!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Retrograde Urethrogram (RUG). In a patient with suspected urethral injury following trauma, a RUG is the essential initial diagnostic step to accurately assess the integrity of the urethra and guide subsequent management, preventing iatrogenic harm.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA retrograde urethrogram involves the gentle instillation of water-soluble contrast into the urethra, followed by fluoroscopic imaging. This technique allows for precise visualization of the urethral lumen, identifying any extravasation of contrast which signifies a urethral tear. This anatomical mapping is crucial as it dictates whether a Foley catheter can be safely placed or if a suprapubic catheter is required, thereby preventing the conversion of a partial urethral injury into a complete transection or the creation of a false passage.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (cystoscopy) (Incorrect): Cystoscopy is an invasive procedure typically reserved for definitive repair or further evaluation after initial imaging, not as the first diagnostic step in acute trauma.\nOption B (folly catheter) (Incorrect): Attempting to pass a Foley catheter in suspected urethral injury is contraindicated as it can worsen the injury, converting a partial tear into a complete one or creating a false passage.\nOption D (fluoroscopic cystogram) (Incorrect): A cystogram primarily evaluates the bladder for injury. While often performed concurrently with a RUG (cystourethrogram), it does not adequately visualize the urethra itself to diagnose a urethral injury.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Injury Type | Initial Diagnostic Step | Key Finding |\n|---|---|---|\n| Suspected Urethral Injury | Retrograde Urethrogram (RUG) | Extravasation of contrast |\n| Suspected Bladder Injury | CT Cystogram (or conventional cystogram) | Extravasation of contrast from bladder |\n| Suspected Ureteral Injury | CT Urogram (or IVP) | Extravasation of contrast from ureter/hydronephrosis |\n| Suspected Renal Injury | CT Abdomen/Pelvis with IV contrast | Parenchymal laceration, hematoma, extravasation of contrast from kidney |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Blood at the meatus? Don't touch that Foley, get a RUG!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a retrograde urethrogram, you would observe extravasation of contrast material outside the urethral lumen, indicating a tear. The location and extent of this extravasation (e.g., within the perineum, extending into the pelvis) help classify the injury (partial vs. complete).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on Urotrauma (2020). Recommends retrograde urethrogram as the initial diagnostic study for suspected urethral injury.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | cystoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | folly catheter | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | retrograde urthrogram | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | fluoroscopic cystogram | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
