  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't TURP a UTI; treat the infection first!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption A, \"Abx for UTI,\" is the most appropriate initial management. Painful micturition (dysuria) in an elderly male is a classic symptom of a urinary tract infection (UTI), making empiric antibiotic therapy the standard first-line approach.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUrinary tract infections are common in elderly males, often exacerbated by factors such as benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) leading to incomplete bladder emptying, or prior instrumentation. Dysuria arises from inflammation of the bladder and urethra. Prompt initiation of appropriate antibiotics is crucial to alleviate symptoms, prevent progression to more severe conditions like pyelonephritis or urosepsis, and improve patient comfort and quality of life.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): A Foley catheter is indicated for urinary retention or bladder outlet obstruction, neither of which is explicitly stated as the primary issue in this scenario. Painful micturition alone does not necessitate immediate catheterization.\nOption C (Incorrect): Cystoscopy and TURP are invasive diagnostic and surgical procedures, respectively. They are typically reserved for confirmed bladder outlet obstruction due to BPH refractory to medical management, or for diagnostic evaluation after initial, less invasive workup. They are not the first-line management for painful micturition.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Common Symptoms | Initial Management | Definitive Management (if applicable) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| UTI | Dysuria, frequency, urgency, suprapubic pain, fever (in severe cases) | Urine culture, empiric antibiotics | Targeted antibiotics based on culture |\n| BPH with retention | Acute inability to void, suprapubic discomfort/pain, palpable bladder | Catheterization (Foley), alpha-blockers | Alpha-blockers, 5-alpha-reductase inhibitors, TURP, UroLift |\n| Bladder stone | Dysuria, hematuria, intermittent urinary stream, suprapubic pain | Imaging (KUB, US, CT), urine analysis | Cystolitholapaxy, open cystolithotomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Dysuria in elderly male? Think UTI first, then obstruction.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor suspected UTI, urinalysis typically reveals pyuria, bacteriuria, and positive leukocyte esterase or nitrites. A urine culture is essential to identify the causative organism and its antibiotic sensitivities. Imaging, such as a renal ultrasound, may be considered if there are recurrent UTIs or suspicion of underlying structural abnormalities.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia (BPH) (2021) recommend evaluating for urinary tract infection in patients presenting with lower urinary tract symptoms (LUTS), which can include dysuria.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Abx for uti | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Foley catheter | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cysoscopy and turp | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
