  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Remove Cushing's tumor? Give hydrocortisone, or face the crisis!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Hydrocortisone. Patients undergoing adrenalectomy for Cushing's syndrome due to an adrenal adenoma require perioperative glucocorticoid replacement to prevent acute adrenal insufficiency from chronic HPA axis suppression.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic hypercortisolism in Cushing's syndrome leads to suppression of the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis. The contralateral adrenal gland, and often the pituitary's ACTH production, become atrophied or suppressed. Upon removal of the cortisol-producing adenoma, the body is suddenly deprived of cortisol, and the suppressed HPA axis cannot immediately resume normal cortisol production. Hydrocortisone, being a glucocorticoid, directly replaces the missing cortisol, allowing the HPA axis to gradually recover over weeks to months, thereby preventing a life-threatening adrenal crisis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Fludrocortisone is a mineralocorticoid, primarily used to replace aldosterone. While important in primary adrenal insufficiency affecting both glucocorticoid and mineralocorticoid production, or after bilateral adrenalectomy, it does not address the acute glucocorticoid deficiency following unilateral adrenalectomy for Cushing's.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hydrocortisone | Fludrocortisone | Dexamethasone |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Class | Glucocorticoid | Mineralocorticoid | Glucocorticoid |\n| Primary Use | Cortisol replacement, anti-inflammatory | Aldosterone replacement | Potent anti-inflammatory, immunosuppressant |\n| Perioperative Use in Cushing's Adrenalectomy | Essential for preventing adrenal crisis | Not typically needed for unilateral adrenalectomy | Can be used as glucocorticoid, but hydrocortisone preferred for physiological replacement |\n| Side Effects | Hyperglycemia, immunosuppression | Hypertension, hypokalemia | Hyperglycemia, osteoporosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always give perioperative glucocorticoids for Cushing's adrenalectomy to prevent crisis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, the right adrenal adenoma would appear as a well-circumscribed mass, typically <6 cm, with characteristic imaging features (e.g., low signal on T1-weighted images, loss of signal on out-of-phase T2-weighted images due to lipid content). Intraoperatively, the surgeon would identify the right adrenal gland, dissect it from surrounding structures (liver, kidney, IVC), and resect the adenoma or the entire gland, ensuring careful hemostasis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Treatment of Cushing's Syndrome (2015) recommend perioperative glucocorticoid coverage for all patients undergoing adrenalectomy for Cushing's syndrome.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hydrocortisone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Fludrocortisone | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
