  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lipase gone wild? Pancreas in peril!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. Increased lipolysis is a hallmark of necrotizing pancreatitis, contributing significantly to local tissue destruction and systemic complications. This process releases free fatty acids that are toxic to pancreatic cells and surrounding tissues.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPancreatitis, especially necrotizing forms, involves the premature activation of pancreatic enzymes within the gland. Lipase, normally secreted to digest dietary fats, becomes activated and attacks the adipose tissue within and around the pancreas. This uncontrolled lipolysis leads to the breakdown of triglycerides into free fatty acids and glycerol. The free fatty acids, particularly in high concentrations, are directly cytotoxic, causing further cellular injury, inflammation, and microvascular damage, which perpetuates the necrotizing process and can lead to fat necrosis and saponification.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Hypoglycemia is generally not a feature of acute pancreatitis; rather, hyperglycemia is common due to stress-induced counter-regulatory hormone release (e.g., glucagon, cortisol) and insulin resistance. Severe pancreatic destruction can lead to endocrine insufficiency, but acute hypoglycemia is rare. \nOption C (Incorrect): Decreased gluconeogenesis is not a primary or characteristic feature of necrotizing pancreatitis. As mentioned, hyperglycemia is more typical due to hormonal imbalances and insulin resistance, not impaired glucose production.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Metabolic Derangement | Mechanism in Pancreatitis | Clinical Consequence |\n| :------------------- | :------------------------ | :------------------- |\n| **Increased Lipolysis** | Premature lipase activation | Fat necrosis, free fatty acid toxicity |\n| **Hyperglycemia** | Stress hormones, insulin resistance | Worsened prognosis, need for insulin |\n| **Hypocalcemia** | Saponification of fat by fatty acids | Tetany, cardiac arrhythmias |\n| **Hypoalbuminemia** | Capillary leak, systemic inflammation | Edema, third spacing |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Uncontrolled lipase activity drives fat necrosis in necrotizing pancreatitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, necrotizing pancreatitis appears as areas of non-enhancing pancreatic parenchyma, often with peripancreatic fat stranding and fluid collections. Fat necrosis can be seen as areas of decreased attenuation within the fat.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013, updated 2020) discuss the pathophysiology and management of necrotizing pancreatitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | increased lipolysis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hypoglycemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Decreased gluconeogenesis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
