  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 MMA injury: Epidural's arterial culprit, biconvex on scan.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Middle Meningeal Artery. Epidural hematomas are typically caused by traumatic rupture of the middle meningeal artery or its branches, which lie between the dura mater and the inner table of the skull.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe middle meningeal artery (MMA) is a branch of the maxillary artery, entering the skull through the foramen spinosum. It runs in a groove on the inner surface of the temporal bone, making it particularly vulnerable to injury from blunt trauma, especially to the temporoparietal region. A skull fracture crossing this groove can lacerate the artery, leading to rapid accumulation of arterial blood in the epidural space, dissecting the dura from the skull.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Pontine arteries supply the pons, deep within the brainstem, and are not associated with epidural hematomas. Injury to these vessels would typically result in intraparenchymal hemorrhage or brainstem stroke.\nOption B (Incorrect): The Basilar artery is a major artery at the base of the brain, supplying the brainstem and cerebellum. Its rupture would cause a subarachnoid hemorrhage or brainstem infarction, not an epidural hematoma.\nOption C (Incorrect): The Anterior cerebral artery supplies parts of the frontal and parietal lobes. While its rupture could lead to subarachnoid or intraparenchymal hemorrhage, it is not the typical source of an epidural hematoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Epidural Hematoma | Subdural Hematoma | Subarachnoid Hemorrhage | Intracerebral Hemorrhage |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Vessel** | Middle Meningeal Artery | Bridging Veins | Aneurysm, AVM | Small arteries/arterioles |\n| **Location** | Between dura & skull | Between dura & arachnoid | Between arachnoid & pia | Within brain parenchyma |\n| **Shape on CT** | Biconvex (lenticular) | Crescent-shaped | Fills sulci/cisterns | Irregular, intraparenchymal |\n| **Onset** | Often rapid (arterial) | Slower (venous) | Sudden \"thunderclap\" | Variable, often acute |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Epidural hematoma = Middle Meningeal Artery = Biconvex on CT.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, an epidural hematoma classically appears as a biconvex (lenticular) hyperdense collection of blood that does not cross suture lines but can cross the falx or tentorium. Intraoperatively, arterial bleeding from the torn middle meningeal artery would be observed, often requiring direct ligation or cauterization.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nGuidelines for the Management of Severe Traumatic Brain Injury, 4th Edition (Brain Trauma Foundation, 2017) recommend prompt surgical evacuation for epidural hematomas meeting specific size and mass effect criteria.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pontine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Basilar | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Anterior cerebral artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Middle meningeal artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
