  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Polyps galore in youth, FAP's the truth!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Familial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP), represented by \"Familial polyp.\" This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the patient's young age (28) and the proctoscopic finding of \"multiple polyps\" in the context of rectal bleeding.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFamilial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP) is an autosomal dominant disorder caused by a germline mutation in the APC gene. It is characterized by the development of hundreds to thousands of adenomatous polyps throughout the colon and rectum, typically appearing in adolescence or early adulthood. Without prophylactic colectomy, nearly 100% of FAP patients will develop colorectal cancer, often by age 40. The presence of multiple polyps on proctoscopy in a young patient with bleeding is a classic presentation, necessitating further workup for FAP.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Diverticulosis) (Incorrect): Diverticulosis is rare in patients as young as 28 and is characterized by outpouchings of the colonic wall, not multiple polyps as the primary finding. Bleeding from diverticula is typically painless and often massive.\nOption C (Crohns) (Incorrect): While Crohn's disease can cause rectal bleeding and may present with inflammatory pseudopolyps, the term \"multiple polyps\" in this context, especially in a young patient, points more specifically to adenomatous polyps characteristic of FAP rather than inflammatory changes.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Familial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP) | Diverticulosis | Crohn's Disease |\n| :------------------ | :----------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------- | :----------------------------------------------- |\n| **Typical Age** | Young adult (teens-30s) | Older adults (>50s) | Any age, bimodal peaks (15-30, 60-80) |\n| **Primary Finding** | Hundreds-thousands of adenomatous polyps | Diverticula (outpouchings) | Transmural inflammation, skip lesions, strictures |\n| **Bleeding** | Common, often chronic | Common, often acute/painless, can be massive | Common, often with diarrhea/abdominal pain |\n| **Malignancy Risk** | Nearly 100% colorectal cancer if untreated | No increased risk from diverticula themselves | Increased risk of colorectal cancer |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Young patient + multiple polyps on scope = FAP until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, FAP is characterized by a carpet of innumerable adenomatous polyps, often numbering in the hundreds to thousands, covering the entire colorectal mucosa. These polyps can vary in size and morphology.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Genetic Testing and Management of Hereditary Gastrointestinal Cancer Syndromes (2015) recommends genetic counseling and testing for individuals suspected of FAP and surveillance colonoscopy starting in early adolescence.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Diverticulosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Familia polyp | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Crohns | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
