  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 In kids, a stable spleen is a happy spleen, keep it in!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nConservative management is the correct approach for this 12-year-old. Pediatric blunt splenic trauma, even with a Grade 3 injury, is typically managed non-operatively due to high success rates and the critical importance of splenic preservation in children.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe pediatric spleen has a remarkable capacity for healing and regeneration, making non-operative management (NOM) highly successful in hemodynamically stable children. NOM avoids the risks associated with surgery, such as anesthesia complications, bleeding, and infection, and crucially preserves the spleen's vital immune function, thereby preventing the lifelong risk of overwhelming post-splenectomy infection (OPSI). The success rate for NOM in stable pediatric patients, even with higher-grade injuries, is exceptionally high.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Splenectomy): Incorrect. Splenectomy is a last resort due to the significant risk of OPSI, especially in children. It is reserved for hemodynamically unstable patients who fail NOM or have ongoing life-threatening hemorrhage.\nOption B (Spleen preserving surgery): Incorrect. While preferable to splenectomy, spleen-preserving surgery (e.g., splenorrhaphy) is an operative intervention. The initial management for a hemodynamically stable child with blunt splenic trauma, even Grade 3, is non-operative; surgery is considered only if NOM fails.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Injury Grade | Hemodynamic Stability | Recommended Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| I-III | Stable | Non-operative management (NOM) |\n| IV-V | Stable | Non-operative management (NOM) (often with close monitoring/angiography) |\n| Any Grade | Unstable | Operative management (Splenorrhaphy if possible, otherwise Splenectomy) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pediatric splenic trauma: Always NOM first if stable, preserve the spleen!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCT scan would show a splenic laceration (4 cm) and a subcapsular hematoma (7 mm). Active extravasation on CT would indicate ongoing bleeding, potentially prompting intervention like angiography or surgery.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Pediatric Surgical Association (APSA) guidelines (e.g., 2017) recommend non-operative management as the standard of care for hemodynamically stable children with blunt splenic trauma, regardless of injury grade.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Splenectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Spleen preserving surgery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Conservative | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
