  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Snuff box pain after a fall? Think scaphoid, don't stall!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The patient's presentation of a fall on an outstretched hand (FOOSH) followed by pain in the anatomical snuff box is the classic clinical hallmark of a scaphoid fracture. This specific symptom directly points to injury of the scaphoid bone.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe scaphoid bone is the most commonly fractured carpal bone, often injured during a FOOSH mechanism where the wrist is hyperextended and radially deviated. Its unique location forming the floor of the anatomical snuff box makes tenderness in this area a highly sensitive and specific sign of fracture. Furthermore, the scaphoid's precarious retrograde blood supply from the radial artery makes it prone to avascular necrosis if not promptly diagnosed and managed.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Colles) (Incorrect): A Colles fracture involves the distal radius, typically presenting with a 'dinner fork' deformity and pain localized to the distal forearm, not specifically the anatomical snuff box.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Scaphoid Fracture | Colles Fracture |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Bone Involved** | Scaphoid (carpal bone) | Distal Radius |\n| **Mechanism** | FOOSH, wrist hyperextension & radial deviation | FOOSH, wrist hyperextension |\n| **Key Clinical Sign** | Tenderness in anatomical snuff box | Dinner fork deformity, pain distal forearm |\n| **Complications** | Avascular necrosis, non-union | Malunion, median nerve compression |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: FOOSH + snuff box pain = scaphoid until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nInitial imaging should include dedicated scaphoid views (PA, lateral, oblique, and scaphoid-specific views) to identify subtle fractures. If X-rays are negative but clinical suspicion remains high, MRI or CT scan is recommended to detect occult fractures or assess for avascular necrosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Scaphoid Fractures (2019). Recommends advanced imaging (MRI/CT) for suspected scaphoid fractures with negative initial radiographs.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Colles | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Scaphoid | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 712219038-Surgery-by-Hamoud.pdf**\n",
